1
00:00:19,269 --> 00:00:21,355
-[birds chirping]
-[pensive music playing]

2
00:01:09,820 --> 00:01:11,989
[Libby] I'm pretty hungry.
I hope we catch some fish soon.

3
00:01:12,072 --> 00:01:13,156
[Matty] Me too.

4
00:01:13,240 --> 00:01:15,951
-Okay, help me wind.
-Wind back?

5
00:01:16,034 --> 00:01:18,287
-Can we turn this one?
-That's what I'm trying to do.

6
00:01:18,370 --> 00:01:22,124
-[music concludes]
-Slowly. Slowly, slowly, slowly, slowly.

7
00:01:22,207 --> 00:01:25,043
-I am doing it slowly.
-Okay, you got it.

8
00:01:25,127 --> 00:01:27,754
Oh, Matty, look! You see that?

9
00:01:27,838 --> 00:01:29,965
-See that big boat out there?
-[Matty] Mm-hmm.

10
00:01:30,048 --> 00:01:32,301
[Libby] She is the prettiest boat
on Whidbey Island.

11
00:01:32,384 --> 00:01:34,052
That's the <i>Morning Star.</i>

12
00:01:34,928 --> 00:01:37,889
Someday when you're big enough,
I'm gonna teach you how to sail.

13
00:01:37,973 --> 00:01:41,310
-It's the best thing there is, sailing.
-Better than fishing?

14
00:01:41,393 --> 00:01:44,438
Yup. But you know what, kiddo?

15
00:01:45,063 --> 00:01:47,858
-I don't think I want you to grow up.
-Why?

16
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:49,776
[Libby] What if you grow up
and marry some beautiful girl?

17
00:01:49,860 --> 00:01:53,155
-Who's gonna go sailing with me then?
-Dad.

18
00:01:54,072 --> 00:01:55,741
Not a chance.

19
00:01:55,824 --> 00:01:58,243
-[light jazz music playing]
-[indistinct chatter]

20
00:02:01,663 --> 00:02:02,789
Thank you so much.

21
00:02:06,460 --> 00:02:08,211
[kids shouting indistinctly]

22
00:02:12,382 --> 00:02:14,926
Nick. Uh. We need to talk.

23
00:02:15,552 --> 00:02:17,179
Always happy to talk to you, Rudy.

24
00:02:17,262 --> 00:02:18,597
-Hey, Warren.
-Uh-huh.

25
00:02:18,680 --> 00:02:21,099
Did you get that notice
from First Seattle today?

26
00:02:21,183 --> 00:02:23,352
Yeah. Yeah,
as a matter of fact, I did. [chuckles]

27
00:02:23,435 --> 00:02:25,312
Good. Then you know.

28
00:02:25,812 --> 00:02:29,941
-We've got a real problem.
-First Seattle is not a problem, Rudy.

29
00:02:30,025 --> 00:02:32,569
These martinis are a problem. Do you mind?

30
00:02:32,653 --> 00:02:35,614
-Not at all.
-Where were we? All right, First Seattle.

31
00:02:36,823 --> 00:02:37,783
Mommy?

32
00:02:38,784 --> 00:02:39,826
Hey, kiddo.

33
00:02:41,244 --> 00:02:43,413
-How's it going?
-Hand off.

34
00:02:43,497 --> 00:02:45,666
[both grunting]

35
00:02:45,749 --> 00:02:48,085
Oh, you sack of potatoes. Ay-yi-yi.

36
00:02:48,210 --> 00:02:49,753
Have you been carrying him
around the whole party?

37
00:02:49,836 --> 00:02:52,839
-Yeah.
-We're never gonna marry you off, Angie.

38
00:02:52,923 --> 00:02:54,424
Mm, yes.

39
00:02:55,884 --> 00:02:56,802
Picasso.

40
00:02:58,095 --> 00:03:01,807
-Blue period.
-[Nick] The artist's name is Kandinsky.

41
00:03:02,974 --> 00:03:04,393
Wassily Kandinsky.

42
00:03:04,935 --> 00:03:08,397
He was German,
of Russian extraction, 1866 to 1944.

43
00:03:09,731 --> 00:03:12,067
And by the way,
Picasso's Blue period was figurative,

44
00:03:12,150 --> 00:03:13,777
and ended in 1904.

45
00:03:14,528 --> 00:03:17,989
And these watercolors are abstract,
done in 1911.

46
00:03:22,786 --> 00:03:25,205
[scoffs] Picasso.

47
00:03:25,831 --> 00:03:27,082
[indistinct chatter]

48
00:03:28,333 --> 00:03:30,711
Everyone pipe down.
I'm about to give a speech.

49
00:03:31,461 --> 00:03:33,797
Thank you for coming.
I always say the sign of a good party

50
00:03:33,880 --> 00:03:36,341
is when I'm having a better time
than anyone else, but…

51
00:03:36,425 --> 00:03:38,802
Now is the time
when you're expected to ante up…

52
00:03:38,885 --> 00:03:41,263
For drinking all my liquor,
and eating all my food,

53
00:03:41,346 --> 00:03:43,849
And spilling tomato sauce on my couch,

54
00:03:43,932 --> 00:03:45,726
-Bobby Long.
-[guests] Ooh--

55
00:03:45,809 --> 00:03:48,729
-What, you didn't think I saw you?
-[guests laughs]

56
00:03:49,479 --> 00:03:51,773
-Oh, he's insufferable.
-[Nick] Now, we are here to raise…

57
00:03:51,857 --> 00:03:53,316
-I know it.
-…a vast sum of money

58
00:03:53,400 --> 00:03:54,401
for the Small Frye School.

59
00:03:55,527 --> 00:03:58,822
So, while you are reaching
for your checkbooks,

60
00:03:59,740 --> 00:04:02,492
it gives me great pleasure
to introduce Mrs. Rebecca Tingley,

61
00:04:02,576 --> 00:04:07,247
Our totally ravishing,
and completely adorable headmistress.

62
00:04:07,330 --> 00:04:09,791
[guests applauding, whistling]

63
00:04:10,459 --> 00:04:12,919
Mr. Parsons, thank you. [chuckles]

64
00:04:13,670 --> 00:04:16,630
First of all, I'd like to start
by introducing a few members

65
00:04:16,714 --> 00:04:18,925
-of my staff to you today.
-Oh, God.

66
00:04:19,551 --> 00:04:24,848
I give you our dedicated teacher
and head of admissions, Miss Angela Green.

67
00:04:24,931 --> 00:04:28,101
-[guests cheering, applauding]
-Yay!

68
00:04:28,185 --> 00:04:32,189
-[Matty speaking indistinctly]
-Me!

69
00:04:40,947 --> 00:04:42,365
What are you thinking about?

70
00:04:45,243 --> 00:04:49,164
-Was I always as rude as I am now?
-[giggles] Absolutely.

71
00:04:50,499 --> 00:04:52,250
-[chuckles, kisses]
-[kisses]

72
00:05:00,133 --> 00:05:01,092
Hi.

73
00:05:01,968 --> 00:05:03,136
Come have a seat.

74
00:05:13,730 --> 00:05:15,899
Angela, do you think
we ought to break the news to her?

75
00:05:15,982 --> 00:05:19,110
I suppose it's better she hears it from us
than from someone else.

76
00:05:19,194 --> 00:05:21,196
She's not gonna be happy about it.

77
00:05:21,738 --> 00:05:22,906
What's up, guys?

78
00:05:24,866 --> 00:05:25,992
Close your eyes.

79
00:05:26,743 --> 00:05:27,619
Close 'em.

80
00:05:31,164 --> 00:05:33,124
Okay, now, stand up.

81
00:05:33,959 --> 00:05:35,168
Keep 'em closed.

82
00:05:36,628 --> 00:05:40,215
-[humming]
-[light-hearted music playing]

83
00:05:43,593 --> 00:05:45,971
Now, Libby, what is your favorite thing?

84
00:05:46,054 --> 00:05:48,765
-Me?
-Not even close.

85
00:05:50,308 --> 00:05:51,434
All right, open.

86
00:05:55,605 --> 00:05:57,649
I heard Sean Gittman
was thinking of selling.

87
00:05:57,732 --> 00:05:59,359
I made him an offer,

88
00:05:59,442 --> 00:06:01,444
and he agreed
to let us take her out for the weekend.

89
00:06:01,528 --> 00:06:03,238
And if you like it, it's yours.

90
00:06:03,989 --> 00:06:06,408
-If I like it? [chuckles]
-Mm-hmm.

91
00:06:07,367 --> 00:06:09,077
[Libby] Honey, we can't afford that.

92
00:06:09,160 --> 00:06:11,371
[Nick] When have I ever let that
get in my way? Come on.

93
00:06:11,454 --> 00:06:13,540
-[laughs]
-Huh?

94
00:06:14,249 --> 00:06:15,542
What about Matty?

95
00:06:15,625 --> 00:06:18,044
I'll take care of him.
We'll have a great time.

96
00:06:19,504 --> 00:06:21,214
You hate to sail.

97
00:06:22,257 --> 00:06:23,300
I can learn.

98
00:06:26,678 --> 00:06:28,179
-[chuckles]
-Huh?

99
00:06:28,263 --> 00:06:29,180
[both kiss]

100
00:06:30,348 --> 00:06:31,766
[glorifying music playing]

101
00:06:53,204 --> 00:06:57,167
Generally, wine like this
needs time to breathe.

102
00:06:57,959 --> 00:07:01,254
But I don't know,
I don't think we should wait.

103
00:07:03,673 --> 00:07:04,966
I don't see land.

104
00:07:08,053 --> 00:07:09,220
So where is it?

105
00:07:11,014 --> 00:07:13,475
Alaska's over that way,
Japan is straight ahead,

106
00:07:13,558 --> 00:07:15,769
and Australia's somewhere to the left.

107
00:07:16,645 --> 00:07:18,605
Where would you like to go?

108
00:07:18,688 --> 00:07:19,981
Bed.

109
00:07:20,857 --> 00:07:22,484
That can be arranged.

110
00:07:30,867 --> 00:07:32,494
-[Libby sighing]
-[music concludes]

111
00:07:32,577 --> 00:07:37,082
[Libby gasping, moaning softly]

112
00:07:40,669 --> 00:07:42,837
[both giggling]

113
00:07:52,347 --> 00:07:56,226
-[both grunt]
-[Libby moaning]

114
00:08:01,564 --> 00:08:03,400
[breathing heavily]

115
00:08:04,985 --> 00:08:07,612
-[chuckles, kisses]
-[kisses]

116
00:08:07,696 --> 00:08:09,572
We should do this more often.

117
00:08:10,824 --> 00:08:13,243
What do you mean?
Buy expensive sailboats?

118
00:08:13,994 --> 00:08:15,196
-[chuckles]
-If this is what happens,

119
00:08:15,296 --> 00:08:17,247
-I'll buy another one tomorrow.
-[chuckles]

120
00:08:18,581 --> 00:08:23,795
No, go away, just the two of us,
with nobody else around.

121
00:08:24,504 --> 00:08:25,380
[groans]

122
00:08:28,675 --> 00:08:31,761
-I'll drink to that. [kisses]
-[kisses]

123
00:08:33,929 --> 00:08:36,890
[indistinct banging, squeaking]

124
00:08:41,062 --> 00:08:42,063
Nick?

125
00:08:47,444 --> 00:08:48,486
Nick?

126
00:08:52,282 --> 00:08:54,951
Oh, my God. Nick?

127
00:08:58,788 --> 00:09:01,041
-[shouting] Nick?
-[suspenseful music playing]

128
00:09:07,338 --> 00:09:09,132
[whimpers]

129
00:09:13,386 --> 00:09:16,181
Nick? Ni--

130
00:09:16,890 --> 00:09:19,809
Oh, my God. [whimpers]

131
00:09:30,111 --> 00:09:31,571
[waves crashing]

132
00:09:35,408 --> 00:09:37,410
Nick? [whimpering]

133
00:09:39,746 --> 00:09:44,209
[gasping, moaning]

134
00:09:45,794 --> 00:09:49,631
[screaming] Nick! Nick!

135
00:09:51,716 --> 00:09:54,511
Nick! [sobbing] Oh, my God.

136
00:09:56,930 --> 00:09:59,974
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

137
00:10:00,642 --> 00:10:02,519
-[ship horn blaring]
-Nick?

138
00:10:04,437 --> 00:10:07,482
[coast guard on P.A.]
<i>Morning Star,</i> this is the Coast Guard.

139
00:10:07,565 --> 00:10:10,401
Put the knife down, ma'am, and step away.

140
00:10:10,485 --> 00:10:15,824
I-- I don't-- I don't know--
I don't know where my husband is!

141
00:10:16,908 --> 00:10:19,702
[reporter] …an around-the-clock search
for local businessman

142
00:10:19,786 --> 00:10:23,081
Nick Parsons, who disappeared
in these waters off Whidbey Island.

143
00:10:23,164 --> 00:10:25,875
-[motorboat engine revving]
-[indistinct chatter]

144
00:10:31,673 --> 00:10:33,508
[cop] All right, tie it off.

145
00:10:35,969 --> 00:10:37,762
-Hey, Cutter.
-[Cutter] Hey, Tom.

146
00:10:37,846 --> 00:10:39,305
What have you got for me?

147
00:10:41,224 --> 00:10:43,685
[indistinct chatter]

148
00:10:53,319 --> 00:10:55,530
-[Libby] Anything?
-No.

149
00:10:56,156 --> 00:10:58,700
Cutter, please don't let them give up.
He's very strong.

150
00:10:58,783 --> 00:11:01,661
-[Cutter] Libby. L-- Libby.
-He's a very strong man.

151
00:11:04,956 --> 00:11:05,832
[gasping]

152
00:11:05,915 --> 00:11:08,710
The raft and life preservers
are all on board.

153
00:11:09,627 --> 00:11:13,256
These guys,
they tracked the wind, currents--

154
00:11:14,299 --> 00:11:15,884
Uh… Nothing.

155
00:11:17,135 --> 00:11:21,181
The water temperature overnight
was 51 degrees.

156
00:11:21,764 --> 00:11:25,518
-That's cold. That's really cold.
-[gasping, crying]

157
00:11:26,436 --> 00:11:29,189
-Cutter, I can't breathe!
-Just put your head down.

158
00:11:29,272 --> 00:11:32,775
Yeah, that's it.
Deep breaths. Big breaths.

159
00:11:36,446 --> 00:11:38,573
-[cries]
-[shushes]

160
00:11:47,165 --> 00:11:49,542
[waves crashing]

161
00:12:02,555 --> 00:12:03,723
[indistinct chatter over radio]

162
00:12:03,806 --> 00:12:06,643
-Mommy, look!
-[car doors slamming]

163
00:12:15,318 --> 00:12:16,319
Hi, kiddo.

164
00:12:19,822 --> 00:12:20,782
Hey, Bobby.

165
00:12:24,244 --> 00:12:28,957
Hey, Libby. [sighs]
Um… Well Cutter, he, uh--

166
00:12:29,499 --> 00:12:32,001
He asked me to come by
and talk to you, you know.

167
00:12:32,085 --> 00:12:34,921
Just, um, not as an attorney,
just as a friend.

168
00:12:37,382 --> 00:12:40,301
The inquest was held this morning,
and they reviewed all the evidence,

169
00:12:40,385 --> 00:12:44,597
and Nick, uh, well,
he's officially been declared dead.

170
00:12:46,349 --> 00:12:48,726
[Bobby] Now, Libby, they, um--

171
00:12:49,477 --> 00:12:52,355
They've determined
it was a "wrongful death," and you--

172
00:12:54,023 --> 00:12:58,069
Oh, Jesus, you-- you're being
formally charged with his murder.

173
00:12:58,152 --> 00:12:59,779
-[laughs]
-[Bobby] I am here to advise you,

174
00:12:59,862 --> 00:13:02,740
make no statements
whatsoever to the sheriff.

175
00:13:04,909 --> 00:13:06,244
[Cutter] I'm sorry, Libby.

176
00:13:12,166 --> 00:13:13,626
[Libby scoffing] Cutter!

177
00:13:14,627 --> 00:13:16,713
Not in front of my kid, okay?

178
00:13:21,050 --> 00:13:22,176
[tense music playing]

179
00:13:28,474 --> 00:13:31,602
[keys jangling]

180
00:13:40,278 --> 00:13:41,863
[music concludes]

181
00:13:44,866 --> 00:13:48,494
I'm sorry, Libby.
Uh… The judge denied us bail.

182
00:13:52,665 --> 00:13:54,375
[opening briefcase]

183
00:13:59,339 --> 00:14:01,090
Can Angie keep looking after Matty?

184
00:14:04,010 --> 00:14:07,347
Good. Okay, uh-- [sighs]

185
00:14:07,430 --> 00:14:11,142
Let's, uh, take a look at this,
see what we can do.

186
00:14:11,225 --> 00:14:14,103
Bobby. Here's what I think happened.

187
00:14:15,772 --> 00:14:17,690
I had some wine, okay?

188
00:14:18,983 --> 00:14:21,611
And I fell asleep.
It must have been the sun.

189
00:14:22,153 --> 00:14:26,199
And maybe Nick was trying
to cut a snagged line or something,

190
00:14:26,282 --> 00:14:31,287
because the knife
from the galley was on deck.

191
00:14:31,954 --> 00:14:35,208
And-- and maybe the boat
pitched or something,

192
00:14:36,125 --> 00:14:37,418
and he cut himself.

193
00:14:38,169 --> 00:14:42,423
And he tried to come downstairs.
He tried to come below to wake me up.

194
00:14:49,263 --> 00:14:50,932
[sighs]

195
00:14:51,849 --> 00:14:53,184
[chuckles]

196
00:14:55,978 --> 00:14:58,106
I quit these things when I met Nick.

197
00:14:59,899 --> 00:15:02,318
It'll be all right. I promise you.

198
00:15:04,153 --> 00:15:05,071
So.

199
00:15:06,155 --> 00:15:08,825
Why don't we take a look
at this First Guarantee life?

200
00:15:09,450 --> 00:15:10,410
Now…

201
00:15:11,202 --> 00:15:15,832
You both bought life insurance policies
from the company around four months ago.

202
00:15:18,042 --> 00:15:20,837
-And you are the beneficiary.
-I'm his wife.

203
00:15:21,337 --> 00:15:23,423
Libby, you know this policy
is worth two million?

204
00:15:24,298 --> 00:15:27,051
Nick wanted to make sure that
if anything happened to him, we'd be okay.

205
00:15:27,135 --> 00:15:29,554
I'm afraid, he jury may feel
there's a big difference

206
00:15:29,637 --> 00:15:33,266
between "okay" and two million dollars.
They may see it as a motive.

207
00:15:33,349 --> 00:15:35,878
-Is that what they're saying out there?
-No, no one is saying that.

208
00:15:35,976 --> 00:15:37,729
I don't think
we have to be concerned about--

209
00:15:37,854 --> 00:15:39,430
That I killed Nick for money?

210
00:15:40,690 --> 00:15:41,816
[scoffs]

211
00:15:44,569 --> 00:15:46,779
I mean, I know we had some problems,
and Nick worried,

212
00:15:46,863 --> 00:15:48,823
-But we were okay!
-[Bobby] Libby!

213
00:15:48,906 --> 00:15:51,534
Two of his investors were suing him
for embezzlement.

214
00:15:52,076 --> 00:15:54,704
First Seattle issued a lien
on all of his real estate properties,

215
00:15:54,787 --> 00:15:56,747
Your personal possessions--

216
00:15:56,831 --> 00:15:58,833
Now, Nick's death means
all these problems disappear

217
00:15:58,916 --> 00:16:03,588
behind a corporate shield,
leaving you with two million dollars.

218
00:16:06,549 --> 00:16:08,384
Do you think I killed him?

219
00:16:08,468 --> 00:16:12,180
That's the first rule of being a lawyer.
What we think doesn't matter.

220
00:16:12,263 --> 00:16:13,973
It matters to me.

221
00:16:17,393 --> 00:16:20,188
No. Of course.
I don't think you killed him.

222
00:16:24,108 --> 00:16:27,278
[prosecutor] <i>Petty Officer Young,</i>
<i>what was the condition…</i>

223
00:16:27,361 --> 00:16:31,115
of the <i>Morning Star's </i>marine band radio
when you had a chance to inspect it?

224
00:16:31,199 --> 00:16:33,493
The handset cord had been cut.

225
00:16:33,576 --> 00:16:37,121
And as you initially
approached the sailboat,

226
00:16:38,247 --> 00:16:39,290
what did you see?

227
00:16:40,124 --> 00:16:42,126
Mrs. Parsons was holding a knife.

228
00:16:42,210 --> 00:16:44,295
[audience murmuring]

229
00:16:45,505 --> 00:16:49,133
I show you state's exhibit number four.

230
00:16:49,926 --> 00:16:52,428
[Nick's voice on radio]
<i>Uh… Mayday. Mayday.</i>

231
00:16:53,262 --> 00:16:54,847
<i>This is, uh, the </i>Morning Star.

232
00:16:54,931 --> 00:16:57,266
[operator]
<i>Sate your emergency, </i>Morning Star.

233
00:16:57,350 --> 00:17:02,230
[Nick] <i>I've been stabbed.</i>
<i>I'm bleeding, uh-- Oh, Jesus.</i>

234
00:17:02,813 --> 00:17:05,233
<i>My na-- my name's, uh, Nicholas Parsons.</i>

235
00:17:05,316 --> 00:17:08,903
-[operator] <i>State your position?</i>
-[Nick] <i>I don't know, man.</i>

236
00:17:08,986 --> 00:17:13,741
<i>Uh… Three miles northwest of,</i>
<i>uh, of Whidbey Island, I guess.</i>

237
00:17:14,367 --> 00:17:18,162
<i>-Oh, God! Oh, God!</i>
-[button clicks]

238
00:17:18,246 --> 00:17:22,415
Mrs. Parsons, you've heard the testimony
presented to this court,

239
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:23,751
and your explanation is

240
00:17:23,834 --> 00:17:26,503
that somebody must have
come aboard the <i>Morning Star.</i>

241
00:17:27,088 --> 00:17:28,089
That's right.

242
00:17:28,881 --> 00:17:32,218
Well, let's, uh,
consider all the possibilities.

243
00:17:33,052 --> 00:17:38,558
Maybe a band of pirates.
Or aliens! Did aliens murder your husband?

244
00:17:39,308 --> 00:17:43,354
No. Aliens weren't beneficiaries
in your husband's life insurance policy.

245
00:17:43,437 --> 00:17:46,774
-Objection. Your honor, the prosecutor--
-Overruled.

246
00:17:47,316 --> 00:17:49,986
-I told you what happened.
-Yes, you did.

247
00:17:50,069 --> 00:17:53,364
-You told us, that you were asleep.
-Yes.

248
00:17:53,447 --> 00:17:56,117
Maybe you were sleepwalking
when you stabbed your husband--

249
00:17:56,200 --> 00:17:57,451
[Bobby] Objection. Please.

250
00:17:57,535 --> 00:18:00,371
Is Miss Halliwell questioning the witness,
or making a closing argument?

251
00:18:00,454 --> 00:18:01,455
Withdrawn.

252
00:18:02,498 --> 00:18:07,795
I didn't kill my husband!
I loved my husband. [sobs]

253
00:18:08,421 --> 00:18:15,136
[cries] Bobby, I did not kill my husband!

254
00:18:15,845 --> 00:18:20,641
You have to believe me. [sobs echo, fades]

255
00:18:25,563 --> 00:18:27,648
[telephone ringing]

256
00:18:34,572 --> 00:18:36,115
I'm-- I'm sorry, Libby.

257
00:18:38,534 --> 00:18:40,328
It's not your fault, Bobby.

258
00:18:41,871 --> 00:18:45,291
[Matty hums]

259
00:18:47,126 --> 00:18:48,377
[door closes]

260
00:18:52,006 --> 00:18:53,841
I wanna ask you something, Angie.

261
00:18:57,303 --> 00:18:59,221
I'd like you to adopt my son.

262
00:19:00,973 --> 00:19:04,935
-No, Lib, I can't do that. Not to you.
-I've thought it through.

263
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:09,440
I barely survived my parents' house.
I'm not gonna put him there.

264
00:19:10,399 --> 00:19:12,568
[Matty continues humming]

265
00:19:12,652 --> 00:19:13,778
[Libby] Money won't be a problem

266
00:19:13,861 --> 00:19:16,322
because there's the two million dollars
from the life insurance,

267
00:19:16,405 --> 00:19:18,991
and it's going
into a trust fund in his name.

268
00:19:19,075 --> 00:19:22,745
-It isn't about money.
-[whispers] I know.

269
00:19:22,828 --> 00:19:27,667
-[Matty muttering softly]
-Matty loves you.

270
00:19:31,545 --> 00:19:33,964
We can't let him become
a ward of the State.

271
00:19:34,048 --> 00:19:36,676
[Matty mimics gunfire sounds]

272
00:19:38,594 --> 00:19:41,013
[hums]

273
00:19:47,853 --> 00:19:49,271
[softly] Thank you.

274
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:54,860
Hey, kiddo. Come see me.

275
00:19:56,612 --> 00:19:58,656
-[chuckles]
-[dramatic music playing]

276
00:20:00,241 --> 00:20:03,411
You're gonna go stay
with Angie for a while. Okay, kiddo?

277
00:20:03,494 --> 00:20:04,495
Okay.

278
00:20:05,204 --> 00:20:07,456
And you're gonna have lots of fun.

279
00:20:09,125 --> 00:20:12,294
And I know
you're gonna be a good boy, right?

280
00:20:12,378 --> 00:20:13,754
Yes, mommy.

281
00:20:15,047 --> 00:20:19,552
And as soon as all this is over,
we'll be together again.

282
00:20:21,762 --> 00:20:25,266
That's a promise, kiddo. Okay?

283
00:20:25,349 --> 00:20:27,309
[pensive music playing]

284
00:20:27,393 --> 00:20:28,728
I love you.

285
00:20:31,105 --> 00:20:32,189
I love you, too.

286
00:20:37,987 --> 00:20:39,029
[kisses]

287
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:11,479
[siren blaring]

288
00:21:13,439 --> 00:21:15,274
[siren continues]

289
00:21:18,778 --> 00:21:21,280
-[inmates chatting indistinctly]
-[music concludes]

290
00:21:28,913 --> 00:21:31,665
-Who's this?
-[Evelyn] Rich bitch from Whidbey Island.

291
00:21:32,792 --> 00:21:36,170
-She ain't gonna make it.
-What do you think? A year?

292
00:21:36,879 --> 00:21:39,924
Five cartons says she offs herself
inside of six months.

293
00:21:40,966 --> 00:21:43,093
-Deal.
-Get away from me.

294
00:21:43,177 --> 00:21:45,679
Hey, take it easy.
We're your new best friends.

295
00:21:45,763 --> 00:21:48,641
Heard you did your husband.
Probably deserved it.

296
00:21:49,225 --> 00:21:50,392
Mine did.

297
00:21:53,312 --> 00:21:55,564
[indistinct chatter, coughing]

298
00:22:05,449 --> 00:22:07,618
[indistinct chatter, laughing]

299
00:22:08,994 --> 00:22:12,248
[overlapping conversations]

300
00:22:15,960 --> 00:22:18,420
[Libby]
I know what a pain it is to get here.

301
00:22:18,504 --> 00:22:22,132
-I taught him how to say the ABC's.
-[Libby] Is that true?

302
00:22:22,216 --> 00:22:23,509
-Sing it, Matty. Go!
-Yes.

303
00:22:23,592 --> 00:22:25,594
Did you learn the alphabet, sweetie?

304
00:22:25,678 --> 00:22:27,680
-Yeah.
-[Libby] Can you tell me?

305
00:22:27,763 --> 00:22:32,101
-[sings]<i> ♪ A, B, C, D E, F, G… ♪</i>
-[laughs]

306
00:22:32,351 --> 00:22:35,855
<i>♪ H, I , J, K, L, M, N, O, P ♪</i>

307
00:22:36,146 --> 00:22:38,983
<i>♪ Q, R, S T, U ♪</i>

308
00:22:39,650 --> 00:22:43,320
<i>♪ W, X, Y and Z ♪</i>

309
00:22:43,654 --> 00:22:47,533
<i>♪ Now I know my ABC's ♪</i>

310
00:22:47,950 --> 00:22:51,495
<i>♪ Next time won't you sing with me ♪</i>

311
00:22:59,378 --> 00:23:00,588
[somber music playing]

312
00:23:03,716 --> 00:23:06,635
-[phone line ringing]
-Give it up. Come on.

313
00:23:06,719 --> 00:23:10,222
-Get off the phone, bitch. Jesus.
-[ringing continues]

314
00:23:18,522 --> 00:23:20,900
[weeps]

315
00:23:29,074 --> 00:23:31,368
[weeping continues]

316
00:23:39,960 --> 00:23:42,504
-[indistinct chatter]
-[music concludes]

317
00:23:46,884 --> 00:23:48,677
Whoa, you're low on cigarettes.

318
00:23:48,761 --> 00:23:52,222
If you wanna make any friends,
I advise you buy another pack fast.

319
00:23:52,306 --> 00:23:55,517
On account of your personality,
it ain't the best I've ever seen.

320
00:23:56,143 --> 00:23:59,271
Hear you're tryin' to reach your friend,
the one with your boy.

321
00:23:59,772 --> 00:24:02,191
Yeah, I can't find 'em.
They disappeared.

322
00:24:02,274 --> 00:24:05,611
Oh, hon,
if you could disappear that easy,

323
00:24:05,694 --> 00:24:07,529
believe you me,
I wouldn't be here right now.

324
00:24:07,613 --> 00:24:10,950
-[chuckles] Me either.
-[whistle blowing indistinctly]

325
00:24:12,743 --> 00:24:15,287
Think. Use your head.

326
00:24:16,163 --> 00:24:18,332
There's gotta be a way to track 'em down.

327
00:24:23,128 --> 00:24:26,006
[indistinct chatter, laughing continues]

328
00:24:29,218 --> 00:24:30,761
-[receptionist] <i>Small Fry School…</i>
-[shushes]

329
00:24:30,844 --> 00:24:33,389
<i>-…front office.</i>
-Hello, this is Angela Green calling.

330
00:24:33,472 --> 00:24:35,683
-[receptionist] <i>Angie, it's Jennifer.</i>
-Yes, hi. How are you?

331
00:24:35,766 --> 00:24:38,310
-[receptionist] <i>Good to hear from you.</i>
-Yes, it's nice to hear your voice.

332
00:24:38,394 --> 00:24:41,522
Listen, I haven't gotten
a severance check in a while,

333
00:24:41,605 --> 00:24:43,983
and I was hoping I could verify with you

334
00:24:44,066 --> 00:24:46,402
that you have my correct mailing address
and phone number.

335
00:24:46,485 --> 00:24:48,028
[receptionist] <i>Sure, I'll check.</i>
<i>Can you hold on a sec?</i>

336
00:24:48,112 --> 00:24:50,114
Yes, of course. Thank you.

337
00:24:50,197 --> 00:24:52,741
[indistinct chatter]

338
00:24:53,701 --> 00:24:57,162
[receptionist] <i>Yeah, I have it right here.</i>
<i>Tell me if this is right.</i>

339
00:24:57,246 --> 00:25:03,043
<i>3-3-2-1 Mason Street,</i>
<i>San Francisco, 9-4-1-0-5.</i>

340
00:25:03,669 --> 00:25:06,338
<i>The phone number is 4-1-5--</i>

341
00:25:07,089 --> 00:25:08,674
[telephone ringing]

342
00:25:10,009 --> 00:25:11,593
-[telephone beeps]
-Hello?

343
00:25:11,677 --> 00:25:14,722
-[Libby] <i>Angie? Angie.</i>
-Libby?

344
00:25:14,805 --> 00:25:16,974
I--
I've tried to call you a thousand times.

345
00:25:17,057 --> 00:25:19,560
-Is Matty okay? Where is he?
-[Angie]<i> Yeah, he's fine.</i>

346
00:25:19,643 --> 00:25:21,228
Everything is fine.

347
00:25:21,311 --> 00:25:24,231
What are you doing in San Francisco?
Put him on the phone.

348
00:25:24,314 --> 00:25:26,567
Hey, why are you acting this way?

349
00:25:26,650 --> 00:25:30,237
Because you disappeared,
and I haven't seen my son in a month!

350
00:25:30,320 --> 00:25:33,073
-I was just about to call you.
-[Libby] <i>Oh, bullshit!</i>

351
00:25:33,157 --> 00:25:35,701
How can you move
and not tell me, Angie?

352
00:25:35,784 --> 00:25:37,995
We were coming to see you next week.

353
00:25:38,078 --> 00:25:40,622
Just put Matty on the phone.

354
00:25:40,706 --> 00:25:42,082
[sighs]

355
00:25:45,627 --> 00:25:48,213
Matty? It's mommy. Come say hi.

356
00:25:50,424 --> 00:25:52,342
Come here. Here.

357
00:25:52,968 --> 00:25:56,013
-Hi, mommy.
-Hello, sweetie pie.

358
00:25:56,847 --> 00:25:59,183
How are you, Matty?

359
00:25:59,266 --> 00:26:01,769
[laughs]
I think about you all the time, honey.

360
00:26:01,852 --> 00:26:05,439
I miss you so much.
Are you doing okay, kiddo?

361
00:26:05,522 --> 00:26:06,690
I love you.

362
00:26:07,316 --> 00:26:10,819
Listen, Matty.
I know that this has been really hard

363
00:26:12,029 --> 00:26:15,074
but Angie is gonna bring you
up to see me next week, okay?

364
00:26:15,157 --> 00:26:16,742
[Matty] Yes, mommy.

365
00:26:17,326 --> 00:26:18,744
Daddy!

366
00:26:19,369 --> 00:26:20,788
-[tense music playing]
-Nick?

367
00:26:23,665 --> 00:26:25,042
[mouthing]

368
00:26:26,627 --> 00:26:27,753
Nick?

369
00:26:34,218 --> 00:26:39,014
-[indistinct chatter echoing]
-[shocked gasping]

370
00:26:41,892 --> 00:26:43,644
[coins rattling]

371
00:26:46,271 --> 00:26:47,773
[Nick sighing]

372
00:26:52,861 --> 00:26:55,322
[line beeping]

373
00:27:04,873 --> 00:27:08,001
[indistinct chatter echoing]

374
00:27:33,569 --> 00:27:35,362
[music concludes]

375
00:27:44,538 --> 00:27:46,373
He was in San Francisco last night.

376
00:27:46,456 --> 00:27:49,334
I have a phone number,
but it's already been disconnected.

377
00:27:50,127 --> 00:27:53,297
No, I don't--
I don't have a forwarding address.

378
00:27:53,380 --> 00:27:56,758
He's gone.
Well, don't you have investigators?

379
00:27:56,842 --> 00:27:59,928
Doesn't your company want
to get its two million dollars back?

380
00:28:00,554 --> 00:28:03,807
Why aren't you listening to me?
I am innocent.

381
00:28:03,891 --> 00:28:06,351
[prisoners yelling]
Yeah, you are. Sure, you are.

382
00:28:08,562 --> 00:28:09,730
Hurry up.

383
00:28:14,234 --> 00:28:18,030
["We Wish You A Merry Christmas" playing]

384
00:28:22,868 --> 00:28:24,912
Put some elbow grease
behind that stirring.

385
00:28:24,995 --> 00:28:28,624
-Nobody wants to eat any burnt tapioca.
-Does it smell like it's burning?

386
00:28:29,333 --> 00:28:31,668
Oh, I swear you got shit for brains, girl.

387
00:28:32,461 --> 00:28:34,838
You're in prison. Do you get that?

388
00:28:35,547 --> 00:28:37,716
Nobody wants to listen
to anybody in prison,

389
00:28:37,799 --> 00:28:40,177
so you can just forget
about reopening your case,

390
00:28:40,260 --> 00:28:42,512
or a jail-house appeal. You got that?

391
00:28:42,596 --> 00:28:46,600
They take years,
and they're 95% unsuccessful.

392
00:28:47,684 --> 00:28:49,895
-So, if you want my advice--
-No.

393
00:28:49,978 --> 00:28:52,606
Well, you're gonna get it.
You do your time.

394
00:28:52,689 --> 00:28:54,483
So what are you now, a lawyer?

395
00:28:56,109 --> 00:28:57,402
Once upon a time.

396
00:28:59,780 --> 00:29:01,531
But they tend to disbar murderers.

397
00:29:02,407 --> 00:29:05,494
And here's your Christmas present.
You ready?

398
00:29:05,577 --> 00:29:09,414
Pay attention, because this is best
goddamn advice you ever gonna get.

399
00:29:09,498 --> 00:29:12,751
Ever hear of double jeopardy?
Fifth amendment to the constitution?

400
00:29:12,834 --> 00:29:15,087
Huh? No?
Well, double jeopardy provides that,

401
00:29:15,170 --> 00:29:18,340
"No person may be tried
for the same crime twice." You got that?

402
00:29:19,299 --> 00:29:22,761
Keep stirrin'. The state says
you already killed your husband.

403
00:29:22,844 --> 00:29:25,180
They can't convict you
of it a second time.

404
00:29:25,264 --> 00:29:27,391
That means that when you leave here,

405
00:29:27,474 --> 00:29:31,144
you track him down,
and when you find him you can kill him.

406
00:29:32,271 --> 00:29:35,399
That's right. You can walk
right up to him in Times Square,

407
00:29:35,482 --> 00:29:38,318
put a gun to his head
and pull the fuckin' trigger,

408
00:29:38,402 --> 00:29:41,029
and there's nothin'
anybody can do about it.

409
00:29:43,198 --> 00:29:45,993
Kinda makes you feel
warm and tingly all over, don't it?

410
00:29:48,245 --> 00:29:50,831
-[thrilling music playing]
-That's right. Keep stirrin'.

411
00:30:00,465 --> 00:30:02,342
[grunting]

412
00:30:04,511 --> 00:30:07,097
[exhales]

413
00:30:09,766 --> 00:30:11,643
[thunderclap]

414
00:30:15,897 --> 00:30:19,901
I gotta hand it to you, honey.
It's just sheer hate driving you on.

415
00:30:31,621 --> 00:30:33,540
[music concludes]

416
00:30:34,166 --> 00:30:35,876
Honey, the only way
you're gonna look like that

417
00:30:35,959 --> 00:30:38,170
is if I staple the picture
to your forehead.

418
00:30:38,253 --> 00:30:39,713
Just trust me, okay?

419
00:30:46,261 --> 00:30:50,057
-Matty's eighth birthday, honey.
-[inmate 1] Aw.

420
00:30:50,140 --> 00:30:52,309
-[everyone] Oh--
-[inmate 2] Look at that.

421
00:30:53,810 --> 00:30:55,395
[indistinct chatter, laughter]

422
00:30:57,397 --> 00:30:59,649
[inhales, blows]

423
00:31:01,360 --> 00:31:03,362
[inmates cheering, applauding]

424
00:31:13,038 --> 00:31:15,332
[light-hearted music playing]

425
00:31:16,875 --> 00:31:19,419
You know, Evelyn,
I read that even if a child is separated

426
00:31:19,503 --> 00:31:21,296
from its mother the day it's born,

427
00:31:22,714 --> 00:31:24,383
it never forgets her voice.

428
00:31:26,385 --> 00:31:28,095
Think that's true?

429
00:31:32,307 --> 00:31:33,683
'Course I do.

430
00:31:38,939 --> 00:31:41,358
"I feel like I've grown
these past six years."

431
00:31:41,441 --> 00:31:42,901
"Grown"? Honey, they don't want to hear

432
00:31:42,984 --> 00:31:44,861
that you've turned
into some kind of tree, okay?

433
00:31:44,945 --> 00:31:45,987
So just repeat after me,

434
00:31:46,071 --> 00:31:48,407
"If I could trade places
with my husband, I would."

435
00:31:48,490 --> 00:31:50,992
Ugh. "If I could trade places
with my husband, I would."

436
00:31:51,076 --> 00:31:53,161
That's good. Now throw in a lot of
that born-again-Jesus stuff.

437
00:31:53,245 --> 00:31:54,746
-They like that.
-Listen, listen, listen.

438
00:31:54,830 --> 00:31:56,039
I want you to start with this--

439
00:31:56,123 --> 00:31:59,084
"I'm not sitting in front of you today
to make excuses."

440
00:31:59,167 --> 00:32:00,627
[Libby] I'm not sitting
in front of you today

441
00:32:00,710 --> 00:32:04,339
to try to make any excuses.
I killed my husband.

442
00:32:05,757 --> 00:32:08,885
I've had to live with that every day
for the past six years.

443
00:32:09,386 --> 00:32:11,888
But I swear to you
that I'm a changed person.

444
00:32:11,972 --> 00:32:13,557
Why should we believe you?

445
00:32:14,724 --> 00:32:17,477
[Libby] I don't think
I can ask you to believe me.

446
00:32:17,561 --> 00:32:19,896
All I can really do is believe in myself

447
00:32:21,314 --> 00:32:25,402
and know that if I were given a chance,
I could do something good with my life.

448
00:32:26,236 --> 00:32:27,946
Make up for the wrong I did.

449
00:32:29,865 --> 00:32:32,242
-[indistinct chatter]
-[car horns blowing]

450
00:32:49,468 --> 00:32:52,137
That was cool. Oh, mommy!

451
00:32:52,220 --> 00:32:54,764
-Yeah!
-Hey, hey. Talk to me. [laughs]

452
00:32:54,848 --> 00:32:56,850
Oh, man, did you see that?

453
00:32:58,268 --> 00:33:01,480
[man speaking indistinctly]

454
00:33:04,274 --> 00:33:06,818
…six years telling each other stories

455
00:33:06,902 --> 00:33:09,070
about all the shit
that's been done to you.

456
00:33:09,154 --> 00:33:11,490
A lot of shit's been done to you.
I know that.

457
00:33:11,573 --> 00:33:15,577
But let's imagine that all those people
that did that shit showed up here.

458
00:33:15,660 --> 00:33:18,163
-The man's across the hall.
-Thanks.

459
00:33:18,663 --> 00:33:20,499
Let's imagine that they all showed up here
and apologized.

460
00:33:20,582 --> 00:33:23,627
Would that change the situation
you're in right now?

461
00:33:23,710 --> 00:33:25,712
[man speaking indistinctly]

462
00:33:27,464 --> 00:33:30,675
-[commentator on TV indistinctly]
-Come in.

463
00:33:30,759 --> 00:33:32,761
[commentator on TV indistinctly continues]

464
00:33:34,054 --> 00:33:35,305
[sighs]

465
00:33:39,643 --> 00:33:41,311
I'm Elizabeth Parsons.

466
00:33:41,394 --> 00:33:43,021
What do you have in that box?

467
00:33:49,236 --> 00:33:50,862
Elizabeth Parsons.

468
00:33:52,989 --> 00:33:56,034
The State of Washington
has granted you a conditional parole.

469
00:33:56,117 --> 00:33:56,993
For the next three years,

470
00:33:57,077 --> 00:33:58,912
you will observe
all the rules of this facility,

471
00:33:58,995 --> 00:34:02,457
which means no fighting,
no fornicating, no drinking, no drugs,

472
00:34:02,541 --> 00:34:04,334
no exceptions, no excuses.

473
00:34:04,417 --> 00:34:06,169
-Do you understand that?
-Yes.

474
00:34:07,712 --> 00:34:09,297
This is your social security card.

475
00:34:09,380 --> 00:34:12,300
You will find gainful
and sustained employment.

476
00:34:13,467 --> 00:34:16,012
You are not to carry a firearm
or a weapon of any kind,

477
00:34:16,096 --> 00:34:17,597
especially a knife.

478
00:34:18,389 --> 00:34:19,766
Curfew is at 8:30.

479
00:34:21,101 --> 00:34:23,270
This is my cell phone number.
Do not lose it.

480
00:34:23,353 --> 00:34:25,438
If you think there's a chance
you will be even five minutes late,

481
00:34:25,522 --> 00:34:27,190
you will call me,
I will have you picked up.

482
00:34:27,274 --> 00:34:29,317
Do you understand that? Good.

483
00:34:29,985 --> 00:34:31,570
Any violation of these conditions,

484
00:34:31,652 --> 00:34:35,239
and your get-out-of-jail-free card
will be revoked by me,

485
00:34:35,322 --> 00:34:37,367
and you will return to prison
to serve the remainder of your sentence

486
00:34:37,449 --> 00:34:38,451
and maybe then some.

487
00:34:38,534 --> 00:34:40,704
-Look right here.
-[camera shutter clicks]

488
00:34:46,626 --> 00:34:49,379
[commentator on TV indistinctly]

489
00:34:50,505 --> 00:34:52,047
[sighs, grunts]

490
00:34:54,801 --> 00:34:57,804
-Is this a problem for you?
-No.

491
00:34:57,887 --> 00:35:00,557
Yes, it is.
Do you want to tell me about him?

492
00:35:01,224 --> 00:35:02,559
No.

493
00:35:02,642 --> 00:35:07,063
[scoffs] No.
I'm gonna have trouble with you, Parsons.

494
00:35:07,147 --> 00:35:09,899
No, sir. No, you're not.
I learned my lesson. I just want to--

495
00:35:09,983 --> 00:35:11,818
I'm not interested
in your goddamn contrition.

496
00:35:11,901 --> 00:35:13,945
I'm interested in your behavior.
Get out of here and behave yourself.

497
00:35:14,029 --> 00:35:16,948
-You're in room eight on the second floor.
-[keys jingling]

498
00:35:46,436 --> 00:35:49,939
No, you're, uh-- [chuckles]
You're never gonna get anywhere like that.

499
00:35:50,023 --> 00:35:52,776
-Here.
-[keyboard keys clacking]

500
00:35:54,152 --> 00:35:55,570
[beeps]

501
00:35:57,447 --> 00:35:58,907
Hmm. Nice shampoo.

502
00:35:59,616 --> 00:36:01,284
Now, uh, what are you looking for?

503
00:36:01,368 --> 00:36:03,286
A friend I haven't seen
for a couple of years.

504
00:36:03,370 --> 00:36:05,455
Someone said I should try the Internet.

505
00:36:05,538 --> 00:36:07,457
This a boyfriend?

506
00:36:07,540 --> 00:36:11,086
-Girl.
-Okay. Well, in that case, I'll help you.

507
00:36:11,169 --> 00:36:13,421
[chuckles] Does your friend have e-mail?

508
00:36:14,047 --> 00:36:17,592
-I have no idea.
-Okay, come on. Let's do some surfing.

509
00:36:17,676 --> 00:36:20,929
-So, uh, what's your friend's name?
-Angela Green.

510
00:36:21,012 --> 00:36:22,138
Uh… Zip code?

511
00:36:23,431 --> 00:36:25,850
Hmm. How about a social security number?

512
00:36:26,351 --> 00:36:28,645
That way we could run a credit report,
and it'll give us her address.

513
00:36:28,728 --> 00:36:31,773
Nope. She was a school teacher.

514
00:36:32,857 --> 00:36:35,151
-Done deal.
-[keyboard keys clacking]

515
00:36:42,575 --> 00:36:44,786
-[man] And… voila.
-[beeps]

516
00:36:46,663 --> 00:36:49,207
Now, maybe when this thing
has finished its searching,

517
00:36:49,290 --> 00:36:51,626
we could go to this, uh,
this neat little bar I know

518
00:36:51,710 --> 00:36:54,087
and, uh, you know, have a little drink.

519
00:36:55,296 --> 00:36:56,589
What do you say?

520
00:36:56,673 --> 00:36:59,634
Yeah. I just have to check in
with my parole officer first.

521
00:37:03,106 --> 00:37:04,264
-You've been to jail?
-Actually, prison.

522
00:37:04,347 --> 00:37:06,099
Jail is a different thing.

523
00:37:06,683 --> 00:37:10,270
[laughing] So, what did you do,
not pay your parking tickets?

524
00:37:10,353 --> 00:37:13,732
Oh, no.
I was convicted of murdering my husband.

525
00:37:16,484 --> 00:37:18,778
[chuckling] You're kidding, right?

526
00:37:18,862 --> 00:37:24,743
No, I'm not. Um… "Sliced and Diced,"
the paper called it. Can you believe that?

527
00:37:27,245 --> 00:37:28,747
You're not kidding?

528
00:37:28,830 --> 00:37:32,125
No. I said I wasn't.
But it would be nice to have a drink.

529
00:37:32,208 --> 00:37:34,419
I haven't been out
in a long time. [chuckles]

530
00:37:35,170 --> 00:37:36,755
Ye-- Oh!

531
00:37:36,838 --> 00:37:38,840
Oh, look, I just remembered I have, um,

532
00:37:38,923 --> 00:37:40,759
-this appointment with the--
-See ya.

533
00:37:41,384 --> 00:37:42,802
See ya. Sorry.

534
00:37:44,179 --> 00:37:48,183
Oh. Book. See ya. [clears throat]

535
00:37:49,601 --> 00:37:51,436
[computer beeping]

536
00:37:53,271 --> 00:37:55,315
Oh, my God. [sighs]

537
00:37:59,068 --> 00:38:01,738
So he takes me out for dinner,
and he feeds me <i>escargot.</i>

538
00:38:01,821 --> 00:38:03,573
-Do you know what those are? Snails.
-[gasps] Yeah.

539
00:38:03,656 --> 00:38:05,283
Snails, yuck.

540
00:38:05,366 --> 00:38:07,035
But anyway, the moment
I go to bed with him,

541
00:38:07,118 --> 00:38:09,329
the big asshole dumps me. Gee, man.

542
00:38:09,412 --> 00:38:11,570
[Ruby] Oh, for Christ's sake,
you nit-picking fuck!

543
00:38:11,706 --> 00:38:13,582
[Travis] Ruby, do not insult me
by raising your voice.

544
00:38:13,716 --> 00:38:15,396
I'm standing right here,
and I can hear you just fine.

545
00:38:15,446 --> 00:38:17,295
-[Ruby] All right. Sorry.
-[Travis] By the way, I don't like it

546
00:38:17,378 --> 00:38:18,923
I don't like it
when you call me dirty names.

547
00:38:18,998 --> 00:38:20,824
[Ruby] Please, Mr. Lehman,
don't do this to me, man, okay?

548
00:38:20,924 --> 00:38:21,825
I didn't do nothing!

549
00:38:21,908 --> 00:38:23,210
[Travis] Where were you
this afternoon, Ruby?

550
00:38:23,310 --> 00:38:24,661
[Ruby] I was-- I was at my job.

551
00:38:24,751 --> 00:38:26,679
You were down on pike street
wearing lime-green hot pants

552
00:38:26,763 --> 00:38:28,973
-and fishnet stockings!
-I was on my way to work!

553
00:38:29,057 --> 00:38:30,809
-At McDonald's? In those clothes?
-Yes, that's right.

554
00:38:30,892 --> 00:38:32,602
You haven't been to work in a week!
Get your stuff.

555
00:38:32,685 --> 00:38:35,522
[Ruby] Look, I-- I'm sorry, man.
I won't do it again.

556
00:38:35,605 --> 00:38:37,982
I will never do that shit again.
I promise that.

557
00:38:38,066 --> 00:38:40,443
You blew off your parole.
You're going back. It's that simple.

558
00:38:40,527 --> 00:38:41,653
[women sigh, groan]

559
00:38:41,736 --> 00:38:45,740
You fuck! You fuckin' cocksucker!

560
00:38:45,824 --> 00:38:48,660
-[Travis] You got a dirty mouth, Ruby!
-[Ruby] I want one chance!

561
00:38:48,743 --> 00:38:53,081
I just want one chance!
Goddamn you, motherfucker!

562
00:38:53,164 --> 00:38:55,416
You son of a bitch. You mean fucker.

563
00:38:55,500 --> 00:38:58,503
You send me back there it'll kill me,
you mean son of a bitch!

564
00:38:58,586 --> 00:39:01,339
-[guard] Come on.
-[Ruby] Fuck you! Fucking asshole!

565
00:39:01,422 --> 00:39:04,801
-[all murmuring]
-Show's over. Go to sleep!

566
00:39:04,884 --> 00:39:07,512
[indistinct chatter]

567
00:39:11,975 --> 00:39:13,977
You think I'm a mean son of a bitch?

568
00:39:14,060 --> 00:39:16,020
I think you could have
given her a second chance.

569
00:39:16,104 --> 00:39:18,064
There are no second chances
in this house, baby.

570
00:39:18,147 --> 00:39:20,400
This is the last-chance house.
You try to understand that.

571
00:39:20,483 --> 00:39:22,610
[woman] Yeah. Yeah, we got it.

572
00:39:22,694 --> 00:39:24,654
What the hell is wrong with that guy?

573
00:39:24,737 --> 00:39:28,074
What I heard, the man used to be
some college whatchamacallit.

574
00:39:28,157 --> 00:39:30,535
-Law teacher or something?
-Yeah, that's right. That's right.

575
00:39:30,618 --> 00:39:31,828
You're kidding.

576
00:39:31,911 --> 00:39:34,414
How does a law professor
end up someplace like this?

577
00:39:34,497 --> 00:39:36,583
-'Cause life's a bitch.
-Bitch, my ass.

578
00:39:36,666 --> 00:39:39,127
He got a D.U.I. And totaled his car.

579
00:39:39,210 --> 00:39:41,629
I heard he totaled his wife
and his daughter in that accident.

580
00:39:41,713 --> 00:39:44,132
Girl, you're talkin' shit.
Nobody got killed.

581
00:39:44,215 --> 00:39:45,893
But by the time his wife
got done with him,

582
00:39:45,968 --> 00:39:49,888
I bet he wished he was dead.
Took everything he had. Including the kid.

583
00:39:49,971 --> 00:39:52,098
-Hasn't seen his girl in years.
-[tense music playing]

584
00:39:52,181 --> 00:39:54,267
[indistinct chatter]

585
00:40:37,727 --> 00:40:40,021
Libby, it's wrong of you to be here.
It's very wrong.

586
00:40:40,104 --> 00:40:43,107
I'm sorry to bother you,
but you're my only hope.

587
00:40:43,191 --> 00:40:45,860
-Sharon? No, you put that down, please.
-[children shouting indistinctly]

588
00:40:45,944 --> 00:40:49,739
-Libby, I'm sorry. I can't.
-I want to find my son!

589
00:40:50,573 --> 00:40:54,827
Matty's had six years with Angie.
I mean, think about it, Libby, six years.

590
00:40:55,370 --> 00:40:57,872
Oh, Benjamin, that's a great sand castle.

591
00:40:58,706 --> 00:41:00,333
If you come back into his life right now,

592
00:41:00,416 --> 00:41:03,044
it's just gonna cause
more disruption and-- and pain.

593
00:41:03,544 --> 00:41:06,047
Just think about it, Libby, please?
Think about it.

594
00:41:07,382 --> 00:41:09,092
I just want to see him, Rebecca.

595
00:41:10,051 --> 00:41:12,178
-[sighs]
-Can you give me an address for Angie,

596
00:41:12,261 --> 00:41:15,890
-so I can see him?
-Look, I'm sorry. I really am sorry.

597
00:41:18,434 --> 00:41:21,980
Lauren?
Come on, get down, please. That's it.

598
00:41:27,068 --> 00:41:29,028
[footsteps approaching]

599
00:41:33,074 --> 00:41:35,243
[dog barking]

600
00:41:45,086 --> 00:41:48,089
[barking continues]

601
00:42:02,020 --> 00:42:03,062
[knocking]

602
00:42:06,607 --> 00:42:11,070
-Where's Parsons?
-[sighs] I don't know. Not here.

603
00:42:28,671 --> 00:42:30,923
-[sighs, grunts]
-[file cabinet rattling]

604
00:42:36,971 --> 00:42:38,681
[vehicle pulling up]

605
00:42:38,765 --> 00:42:40,475
[gasps]

606
00:42:44,145 --> 00:42:45,521
[ominous music playing]

607
00:42:47,732 --> 00:42:49,817
[officer] Probably just a raccoon.

608
00:42:50,318 --> 00:42:52,070
[cabinet, keys rattling]

609
00:42:58,743 --> 00:43:01,871
[Libby panting]

610
00:43:15,593 --> 00:43:19,430
[indistinct chatter over radio]

611
00:43:25,061 --> 00:43:26,562
[officer] Check up the stairs.

612
00:43:33,152 --> 00:43:35,113
[doorknob rattling]

613
00:43:45,665 --> 00:43:47,166
[officer] Cutter! Up here!

614
00:43:53,422 --> 00:43:54,715
Shit!

615
00:43:57,426 --> 00:43:59,303
-[Libby grunting]
-[Cutter] I got her.

616
00:44:23,703 --> 00:44:24,954
There she is.

617
00:44:26,831 --> 00:44:29,542
[panting]

618
00:44:36,382 --> 00:44:38,384
[grunts]

619
00:44:53,858 --> 00:44:57,737
[both screaming]

620
00:44:59,614 --> 00:45:03,618
-[Cutter] Shit!
-[both grunting]

621
00:45:21,969 --> 00:45:23,262
[officer grunting]

622
00:45:24,764 --> 00:45:28,726
-[screams, grunts]
-[music concludes]

623
00:45:31,771 --> 00:45:34,690
Jesus Christ, Libby,
what are you doing here?

624
00:45:52,500 --> 00:45:55,544
-[lock unlocking]
-[door opens]

625
00:45:55,628 --> 00:45:58,381
-[door squeaking]
-[indistinct chatter over radio]

626
00:46:10,810 --> 00:46:12,979
Did you have a nice day at the beach?

627
00:46:13,646 --> 00:46:16,482
[buoy bell clanging]

628
00:46:20,486 --> 00:46:22,488
You piss me off, Parsons.

629
00:46:28,661 --> 00:46:31,289
Angela Green, that's the woman
that's got your kid, right?

630
00:46:32,290 --> 00:46:33,958
Can we not talk, please, Lehman?

631
00:46:34,792 --> 00:46:36,711
Okay. All right.

632
00:46:36,794 --> 00:46:39,297
-So why'd she skip town?
-She just skipped town.

633
00:46:39,380 --> 00:46:42,842
Yeah, with your husband, who isn't dead
'cause you didn't kill him? [chuckles]

634
00:46:42,925 --> 00:46:45,177
-Bullshit.
-Okay, I killed my husband.

635
00:46:45,261 --> 00:46:46,470
I chopped him up into little bits,

636
00:46:46,554 --> 00:46:48,222
and dumped him piece by piece
in the Pacific.

637
00:46:48,306 --> 00:46:49,925
-Are you satisfied?
-No. No.

638
00:46:50,001 --> 00:46:52,102
You were a hell of a lot closer
to your kid three days ago

639
00:46:52,201 --> 00:46:53,452
than you are today.

640
00:46:53,552 --> 00:46:57,815
All you had to do was wait three years.
That's all. You fucking idiot.

641
00:47:02,403 --> 00:47:04,697
You cannot know what it is like
to sit in prison for six years

642
00:47:04,780 --> 00:47:07,783
and think of nothing else
in the world but your son.

643
00:47:07,867 --> 00:47:09,744
Did I make the right choice?
You ask the wrong question, Lehman.

644
00:47:09,827 --> 00:47:11,579
I didn't have a choice. Fuck your curfew!

645
00:47:21,672 --> 00:47:24,091
Who's that? Your daughter?

646
00:47:27,511 --> 00:47:30,181
Is that a problem for you, Lehman?

647
00:47:30,890 --> 00:47:33,017
-[car engine turns off]
-I'm going up top.

648
00:47:34,602 --> 00:47:36,228
[car door closing]

649
00:47:43,611 --> 00:47:46,489
[bell ringing]

650
00:47:47,531 --> 00:47:48,532
Don't go anywhere.

651
00:47:54,872 --> 00:47:57,583
[ferry horn blows]

652
00:48:00,711 --> 00:48:02,922
[indistinct chatter]

653
00:48:28,823 --> 00:48:30,825
[indistinct chatter continues]

654
00:48:32,368 --> 00:48:34,036
[woman] Janey, honey, read your book.

655
00:48:37,415 --> 00:48:39,375
[engine starts]

656
00:48:42,628 --> 00:48:44,672
[tires squealing]

657
00:48:46,173 --> 00:48:48,134
Oh! Shit!

658
00:49:07,111 --> 00:49:10,197
[tires squealing]
[chattering]

659
00:49:18,539 --> 00:49:20,749
[indistinct chatter. laughter]

660
00:49:36,307 --> 00:49:37,850
[thrilling music playing]

661
00:49:43,606 --> 00:49:45,483
-[engine revs]
-[tires screeching]

662
00:49:48,944 --> 00:49:50,529
[groans]

663
00:49:53,699 --> 00:49:54,950
[gasps]

664
00:49:58,787 --> 00:50:00,498
[grunting]

665
00:50:02,541 --> 00:50:04,210
[screams]

666
00:50:17,932 --> 00:50:21,268
-Oh, my God!
-[indistinct chatter]

667
00:50:22,144 --> 00:50:24,522
[alarm blaring]

668
00:50:26,065 --> 00:50:28,067
[alarm bell ringing]

669
00:50:33,113 --> 00:50:34,740
[Travis grunting, gasping]

670
00:51:07,481 --> 00:51:10,359
[both gasp]

671
00:51:13,320 --> 00:51:15,781
[grunts]

672
00:51:26,375 --> 00:51:30,671
-[screams]
-[groans, panting, gasping]

673
00:51:37,136 --> 00:51:39,597
[indistinct chatter]

674
00:51:53,277 --> 00:51:55,279
[gasps]

675
00:52:05,706 --> 00:52:08,042
-[crew member 1] I got him!
-[crew member 2] Grab a hold for me.

676
00:52:08,125 --> 00:52:10,336
[indistinct chatter]

677
00:52:15,466 --> 00:52:16,884
[crew member 1] O2 ready.

678
00:52:18,594 --> 00:52:21,180
-[man] Is he all right?
-[ferry crew] I guess he's all right.

679
00:52:21,263 --> 00:52:23,599
[indistinct chatter]

680
00:52:38,280 --> 00:52:40,199
[Karl] Did you voluntarily
give her the gun?

681
00:52:40,282 --> 00:52:42,284
Come on, Karl.
What do you think? Hey! Hey.

682
00:52:42,368 --> 00:52:44,244
-Sorry.
-Were you drinking?

683
00:52:44,328 --> 00:52:46,914
-No, I wasn't drinking.
-It's been known to happen.

684
00:52:46,997 --> 00:52:49,416
-Do you have any idea where she's gone?
-No.

685
00:52:49,500 --> 00:52:51,502
All right. Well, that's about all,
then, isn't it?

686
00:52:51,585 --> 00:52:53,003
-All what?
-[Karl clearing throat]

687
00:52:53,087 --> 00:52:55,631
There'll be an investigation
into your actions today.

688
00:52:55,714 --> 00:52:58,425
I wouldn't hold my breath
about the prospect of keeping your job.

689
00:52:58,509 --> 00:53:00,469
Karl, give me a break. Goddamn.

690
00:53:01,261 --> 00:53:03,347
[traffic whizzing]

691
00:53:03,430 --> 00:53:04,473
[Libby] Thanks a lot.

692
00:53:12,523 --> 00:53:14,566
[birds chirping]

693
00:53:15,359 --> 00:53:17,277
[dirt scraping]

694
00:53:17,361 --> 00:53:19,947
[Libby's Mother]
Sent your father off to the V.F.W.

695
00:53:20,030 --> 00:53:22,408
He'll be playing gin for hours.

696
00:53:22,491 --> 00:53:25,160
-Some things never change.
-[Libby's Mother] Oh!

697
00:53:25,244 --> 00:53:27,579
He's not as bad
as he used to be, you know.

698
00:53:27,663 --> 00:53:29,081
I'm glad for you, Mama.

699
00:53:29,998 --> 00:53:31,250
[Libby's Mother grunts]

700
00:53:41,427 --> 00:53:44,054
I always said
there was good money in tomatoes.

701
00:53:50,060 --> 00:53:51,645
[laughs]

702
00:53:54,565 --> 00:53:56,442
[traffic whizzing]

703
00:54:07,411 --> 00:54:10,914
-[indistinct chatter]
-[soft music playing]

704
00:54:10,998 --> 00:54:13,125
[salesman] So, you're in the market
for a BMW?

705
00:54:13,208 --> 00:54:15,627
-Yeah. Who isn't?
-Well, they're the best.

706
00:54:16,670 --> 00:54:19,006
I decided it was finally time to trade up.

707
00:54:19,089 --> 00:54:20,048
Right.

708
00:54:21,008 --> 00:54:24,136
So why don't you check my credit
and see if I can finance this.

709
00:54:24,219 --> 00:54:26,138
Great. Let me have
your social security number,

710
00:54:26,221 --> 00:54:27,681
and I'll get the ball rolling.

711
00:54:38,776 --> 00:54:42,112
"20, Oriole Terrace, Evergreen, Colorado."
Is that your current address?

712
00:54:42,196 --> 00:54:46,074
20, Oriole Terrace,
Evergreen, Colorado? Sure is.

713
00:54:46,158 --> 00:54:47,826
Didn't you say your name was Angela Green?

714
00:54:47,910 --> 00:54:50,996
-'Cause this says it's Angela Ryder.
-Oh, no. I said Ryder.

715
00:54:51,079 --> 00:54:52,122
Angela Ryder.

716
00:54:52,831 --> 00:54:53,874
What about the car?

717
00:54:54,750 --> 00:54:55,834
[music concludes]

718
00:54:55,918 --> 00:54:59,004
-[indistinct chatter]
-Here, fill this out and come back to me.

719
00:54:59,713 --> 00:55:00,672
How's tricks, Orbe?

720
00:55:02,466 --> 00:55:03,675
No way.

721
00:55:03,759 --> 00:55:06,136
No way, no way.
I've been clean, Mr. Travis.

722
00:55:06,220 --> 00:55:08,430
Oh, I know. I believe you. I do.

723
00:55:08,514 --> 00:55:10,766
What I need is a search
on a lady named Angela Green.

724
00:55:10,849 --> 00:55:13,143
I've got her social security number here.
I'd like you to--

725
00:55:13,227 --> 00:55:15,521
Please. You know I'm not allowed
to give out personal information.

726
00:55:15,629 --> 00:55:17,523
Oh, I'm so-- I shouldn't have
asked you that. I'm sorry.

727
00:55:17,606 --> 00:55:18,649
Uh-huh.

728
00:55:19,525 --> 00:55:21,151
Speaking of giving out
personal information,

729
00:55:21,235 --> 00:55:22,611
does your employer know
you used to perform

730
00:55:22,694 --> 00:55:24,515
the art of fellatio for a living,
went to prison for it,

731
00:55:24,615 --> 00:55:26,156
-and now you're out on parole?
-Okay. Okay. Shut up.

732
00:55:26,240 --> 00:55:28,242
-You're required by law to tell him.
-All right. Okay.

733
00:55:28,325 --> 00:55:29,618
[sighs]

734
00:55:31,620 --> 00:55:33,580
You're looking good, Orbe.

735
00:55:34,706 --> 00:55:35,666
I know.

736
00:55:36,333 --> 00:55:40,337
[orchestral music playing]

737
00:56:23,881 --> 00:56:26,133
-[music fades]
-[intense music playing]

738
00:56:35,309 --> 00:56:37,686
[indistinct chatter]

739
00:56:45,611 --> 00:56:49,156
[dog barking in the distance]

740
00:57:11,929 --> 00:57:13,430
[doorbell rings]

741
00:57:14,139 --> 00:57:16,099
[pistol clicks]

742
00:57:20,646 --> 00:57:22,940
[Sam's mother] Honey, can you get that?

743
00:57:28,445 --> 00:57:29,446
Hi.

744
00:57:36,662 --> 00:57:39,289
-[Sam's mother] Who is it, Sam?
-[Sam] Uh… Some lady.

745
00:57:40,332 --> 00:57:41,375
[music concludes]

746
00:57:41,959 --> 00:57:43,001
May I help you?

747
00:57:44,336 --> 00:57:47,965
I'm looking for my friend, Angela Ryder.
I thought this was her address.

748
00:57:48,048 --> 00:57:51,176
I've never heard of her.
But we've just moved in.

749
00:57:51,259 --> 00:57:53,637
Uh… Maybe you should check
with the woman who lives next door.

750
00:57:53,720 --> 00:57:55,097
She's been here 40 years.

751
00:57:55,180 --> 00:57:56,473
[Libby] Excuse me.

752
00:57:57,849 --> 00:58:01,019
Dearie, whatever you're selling,
I've already got two of them.

753
00:58:01,728 --> 00:58:04,731
[chuckles] I'm just looking
for my friend, Angela Ryder.

754
00:58:04,815 --> 00:58:06,400
She used to live next door.

755
00:58:07,651 --> 00:58:08,819
Oh, I--

756
00:58:09,987 --> 00:58:14,199
I'm sorry to be the one to tell you,
but Angie died in the accident.

757
00:58:15,575 --> 00:58:18,787
It was three or four years ago.

758
00:58:18,870 --> 00:58:20,789
It was one of those awful things.

759
00:58:20,872 --> 00:58:24,418
The, uh, stove, the gas stove
in their house was leaking.

760
00:58:25,043 --> 00:58:27,337
The explosion knocked out
some of my windows,

761
00:58:27,421 --> 00:58:29,756
-and, uh--
-What about the boy?

762
00:58:29,840 --> 00:58:32,968
Matty? He's such a dear child.

763
00:58:33,051 --> 00:58:35,178
No, he and Simon
weren't there when it happened.

764
00:58:36,722 --> 00:58:37,681
Poor Simon.

765
00:58:38,724 --> 00:58:42,519
I've never seen anyone
so… grief stricken.

766
00:58:43,186 --> 00:58:44,312
Oh, I'm sure.

767
00:58:45,272 --> 00:58:49,151
-[indistinct chatter]
-[indistinct announcements over P.A.]

768
00:58:53,697 --> 00:58:56,825
-[somber music playing]
-[whirring, clicking]

769
00:59:09,796 --> 00:59:12,090
[indistinct chatter]

770
00:59:13,091 --> 00:59:14,384
Help me out, kiddo.

771
00:59:19,890 --> 00:59:24,436
It would really help if you could remember
what kind of car she was driving.

772
00:59:24,519 --> 00:59:26,438
-Well, it was an old truck.
-Yeah?

773
00:59:27,606 --> 00:59:30,817
It's, um-- I don't know
what year or make or anything.

774
00:59:30,901 --> 00:59:32,069
Well, what color was it?

775
00:59:32,152 --> 00:59:34,196
[indistinct chatter]

776
00:59:58,637 --> 01:00:02,349
Kandinsky?
It's a bit out of our reach, I'm afraid.

777
01:00:02,432 --> 01:00:05,310
I have a few Picasso
and Chagall lithographs.

778
01:00:05,393 --> 01:00:07,187
-[music concludes]
-Mm, no. It… it's Kandinsky

779
01:00:07,270 --> 01:00:10,107
that I'm particularly interested in,
especially his Blue Rider period.

780
01:00:10,190 --> 01:00:11,066
I love that.

781
01:00:11,983 --> 01:00:16,238
Uh… Well, um… [smacks lips]
Let's check Art Scan.

782
01:00:18,240 --> 01:00:21,284
Kandinskys don't become available
too often, I'm afraid.

783
01:00:21,910 --> 01:00:25,664
Uh… Here's a lovely little Miro.

784
01:00:25,747 --> 01:00:28,083
-It's quite reasonable.
-It really needs to be Kandinsky.

785
01:00:28,166 --> 01:00:30,460
Kandinsky… yes.

786
01:00:31,336 --> 01:00:36,091
Ah! Here is a lovely
1922 Kandinsky lithograph.

787
01:00:36,174 --> 01:00:39,136
-It's not quite the--
-The 1911 is all that interests me.

788
01:00:39,219 --> 01:00:40,804
1911…

789
01:00:40,887 --> 01:00:44,015
[traffic whizzing]

790
01:00:50,856 --> 01:00:53,984
-Stop. There. Yes. Yes, that's it.
-[salesman] What?

791
01:00:54,067 --> 01:00:55,652
I'm afraid we've missed that.

792
01:00:55,735 --> 01:00:57,737
It was sold to a museum
in Munich six months ago.

793
01:00:57,821 --> 01:01:00,824
Do you think you could find who sold it?
Perhaps they have more.

794
01:01:02,284 --> 01:01:04,619
Well, uh, why, yes. Yes, let's see.

795
01:01:05,662 --> 01:01:07,956
-Ah…
-[bell dings]

796
01:01:10,667 --> 01:01:12,335
If you'll excuse me a moment.

797
01:01:18,091 --> 01:01:20,427
Yes, sir. Can I help you?

798
01:01:20,510 --> 01:01:22,804
Well, yes. My name is Travis Lehman…

799
01:01:22,888 --> 01:01:24,055
[dramatic music playing]

800
01:01:39,529 --> 01:01:41,907
[Travis] Actually, I'm looking
for a young lady…

801
01:01:52,459 --> 01:01:53,543
[beeps]

802
01:02:00,759 --> 01:02:03,595
-[car engine starting]
-[window shatters]

803
01:02:06,223 --> 01:02:08,391
[tires squealing]

804
01:02:08,934 --> 01:02:12,354
[indistinct clamor]

805
01:02:20,528 --> 01:02:22,822
-[tires screeching]
-[car horns honking]

806
01:02:37,087 --> 01:02:38,338
[pants]

807
01:02:40,757 --> 01:02:42,550
[tires screeching]

808
01:02:46,554 --> 01:02:50,684
[pants]

809
01:02:51,351 --> 01:02:53,270
She seemed so refined.

810
01:02:53,353 --> 01:02:57,482
I would really like to know
what that woman wanted in your gallery.

811
01:02:57,565 --> 01:03:01,861
-[pants]
-[music concludes]

812
01:03:01,945 --> 01:03:06,574
[airplane engine whirring]

813
01:03:06,658 --> 01:03:13,415
[group singing acapella] <i>♪ Amazing grace ♪</i>

814
01:03:13,957 --> 01:03:17,585
-[indistinct chatter]
-[group] <i>♪ How sweet ♪</i>

815
01:03:17,711 --> 01:03:20,588
<i>♪ The sound ♪</i>

816
01:03:21,589 --> 01:03:25,010
<i>♪ That saved ♪</i>

817
01:03:25,135 --> 01:03:28,763
<i>♪ A wretch ♪</i>

818
01:03:28,930 --> 01:03:34,352
<i>♪ Like me ♪</i>

819
01:03:41,067 --> 01:03:43,445
[mellow music playing]

820
01:03:59,127 --> 01:04:01,504
[indistinct chatter]

821
01:04:20,690 --> 01:04:21,691
Can I help you?

822
01:04:23,777 --> 01:04:24,944
[music concludes]

823
01:04:25,028 --> 01:04:26,821
I'm looking for Jonathan Devereaux.

824
01:04:26,905 --> 01:04:31,284
Mr. Devereaux is out right now.
He'll be back tonight for the party.

825
01:04:31,368 --> 01:04:32,327
Well, is Matty here?

826
01:04:33,536 --> 01:04:35,246
I don't believe I know you, ma'am.

827
01:04:35,330 --> 01:04:37,665
Maybe you'd like to leave a message.

828
01:04:39,876 --> 01:04:43,546
[indistinct chatter]

829
01:04:47,258 --> 01:04:49,844
-[traffic whizzing]
-[car horn honks]

830
01:04:52,514 --> 01:04:55,517
-[indistinct chatter]
-[hotel lobby music playing]

831
01:05:00,730 --> 01:05:02,633
[receptionist] It's certainly a pleasure
having you stay with us

832
01:05:02,758 --> 01:05:04,692
-here at the Monteleone, Mrs. Kritch.
-[Mrs. Kritch] Thank you.

833
01:05:04,776 --> 01:05:08,571
-My suite has a view?
-Your room has a lovely view, Mrs. Kritch.

834
01:05:08,655 --> 01:05:11,324
-And I need a masseuse.
-I'll send Jerome right up.

835
01:05:11,408 --> 01:05:12,283
Bruce?

836
01:05:13,952 --> 01:05:15,620
1420, Mrs. Kritch.

837
01:05:17,038 --> 01:05:18,039
Hello.

838
01:05:33,555 --> 01:05:35,890
I'm sorry. Are you lost?

839
01:05:36,891 --> 01:05:40,186
No. Actually, I'm found.
I just had an hour with Jerome.

840
01:05:41,729 --> 01:05:44,899
Oh. Jerome.
I've heard that he is marvelous.

841
01:05:44,983 --> 01:05:46,109
He's fabulous.

842
01:05:46,192 --> 01:05:48,278
I haven't felt this good
since my husband died.

843
01:05:49,237 --> 01:05:52,323
So, I've got something for tonight,
but I think I need Armani.

844
01:05:53,908 --> 01:05:56,411
Yes. Very good, Mrs…

845
01:05:56,494 --> 01:05:57,954
Kritch. Suite 1420.

846
01:05:58,037 --> 01:05:59,205
Of course.

847
01:06:00,957 --> 01:06:02,459
I'll be charging it to my room.

848
01:06:08,548 --> 01:06:12,427
-[computer beeps]
-Hm. Now, Mrs. Kritch,

849
01:06:12,510 --> 01:06:15,680
I would say that you are a size… four?

850
01:06:15,763 --> 01:06:18,349
-A two.
-Of course.

851
01:06:18,433 --> 01:06:20,727
[indistinct chatter]

852
01:06:29,569 --> 01:06:31,154
There's a guy waiting for you.

853
01:06:41,623 --> 01:06:42,874
Did you catch that thing?

854
01:06:45,251 --> 01:06:46,377
What did you use for bait?

855
01:06:47,504 --> 01:06:49,797
I caught that big bucket-mouth
son of a bitch

856
01:06:49,881 --> 01:06:52,050
off an old rebel lure my daddy left me.

857
01:06:52,675 --> 01:06:54,719
'Course there's buzz bombs, poppers, jigs,

858
01:06:54,802 --> 01:06:57,055
all kinds of things
work back in these waters.

859
01:06:57,931 --> 01:06:59,015
I'm Jim Mangold.

860
01:06:59,098 --> 01:07:02,143
Travis Lehman,
Washington Department of Corrections.

861
01:07:02,227 --> 01:07:03,937
[Jim] What can I do for you?

862
01:07:04,979 --> 01:07:08,024
-[exhales] Who's this?
-That's somebody I'm looking for.

863
01:07:08,942 --> 01:07:10,068
Pretty girl.

864
01:07:10,151 --> 01:07:13,905
Oh, yeah. She's very pretty,
for a convicted murderer. [chuckles]

865
01:07:13,988 --> 01:07:15,365
She jumped parole on me.

866
01:07:18,034 --> 01:07:20,328
[smacks lips] Mr. Lehman,
I'd love to be able to help you, sir.

867
01:07:20,411 --> 01:07:22,080
No, I don't want you guys
to go to any trouble.

868
01:07:22,163 --> 01:07:25,667
I can handle matters. I just came down
as a professional courtesy,

869
01:07:25,750 --> 01:07:27,710
since she's in New Orleans,
and came here to kill

870
01:07:27,794 --> 01:07:29,587
one of your prominent citizens.

871
01:07:30,463 --> 01:07:32,131
And just how is she planning
on doing that?

872
01:07:32,215 --> 01:07:35,760
I don't know. She'll probably use
the .38 special she stole from me.

873
01:07:40,056 --> 01:07:41,140
[shouts] Roy Lee!

874
01:07:41,766 --> 01:07:43,685
Get these in the works now.

875
01:07:46,145 --> 01:07:48,565
-[guest] She looks lovely.
-Invitation, please.

876
01:07:48,648 --> 01:07:49,816
Enjoy your evening.

877
01:07:50,608 --> 01:07:53,027
Good evening. Thank you.

878
01:07:53,111 --> 01:07:55,363
-[indistinct chatter]
-[jazz music playing]

879
01:07:55,446 --> 01:07:58,992
[doorman] Invitations, please.
Yes, I need to see your invitation.

880
01:08:00,410 --> 01:08:01,286
Thank you.

881
01:08:02,620 --> 01:08:03,621
Enjoy your evening.

882
01:08:04,872 --> 01:08:05,915
Your invitation?

883
01:08:07,375 --> 01:08:08,543
[guest] Oh, thank you.

884
01:08:10,378 --> 01:08:12,839
-[doorman] Good evening.
-What a remarkable wrap.

885
01:08:12,922 --> 01:08:14,507
Where on earth did you find that?

886
01:08:14,591 --> 01:08:17,510
The First Lady asked me the same thing
when we stayed at the White House,

887
01:08:17,594 --> 01:08:19,429
-and I wouldn't tell her either.
-[both laugh]

888
01:08:19,511 --> 01:08:21,221
-[doorman] Your invitation, sir?
-I got it right here.

889
01:08:21,305 --> 01:08:22,432
Enjoy your evening.

890
01:08:22,515 --> 01:08:24,225
-Good evening, miss.
-Good evening.

891
01:08:29,229 --> 01:08:31,941
<i>♪ Mention of work makes you go berserk ♪</i>

892
01:08:32,317 --> 01:08:34,193
<i>♪ 'Cause you hate to do a stitch ♪</i>

893
01:08:35,361 --> 01:08:40,073
<i>♪ If you're so smart</i>
<i>How come you ain't rich? ♪</i>

894
01:08:41,075 --> 01:08:43,745
<i>♪ You're out for a ride</i>
<i>On the road to fame ♪</i>

895
01:08:44,078 --> 01:08:46,038
<i>♪ Yet you wind up in a ditch ♪</i>

896
01:08:47,372 --> 01:08:52,002
<i>♪ If you're so smart</i>
<i>Tell me, how come you ain't rich? ♪</i>

897
01:08:53,004 --> 01:08:57,925
<i>♪ Hershey started with a chocolate bar</i>
<i>Wrigley with a stick of gum ♪</i>

898
01:08:58,885 --> 01:09:01,720
<i>♪ Planters took his peanuts</i>
<i>And travelled far ♪</i>

899
01:09:01,804 --> 01:09:03,765
<i>♪ Now tell me what you doin', chum? ♪</i>

900
01:09:04,432 --> 01:09:07,727
<i>♪ I been hearin'</i>
<i>All about all your big ideas ♪</i>

901
01:09:07,810 --> 01:09:10,104
<i>♪ Since you started. What's the hitch? ♪</i>

902
01:09:10,772 --> 01:09:15,859
<i>♪ If you're so smart</i>
<i>How come you ain't rich? ♪</i>

903
01:09:17,069 --> 01:09:18,654
<i>♪ How come you ain't rich? ♪</i>

904
01:09:18,738 --> 01:09:22,116
-[music concludes]
-[guests applauding]

905
01:09:24,993 --> 01:09:28,163
-Good evening, mesdames and messieurs.
-[guests] Good evening!

906
01:09:28,247 --> 01:09:31,917
We're delighted to witness this evening
on this very special occasion

907
01:09:32,001 --> 01:09:34,837
and, as is the custom in New Orleans,

908
01:09:34,921 --> 01:09:37,631
since even before the war
of Northern Aggression…

909
01:09:37,715 --> 01:09:39,133
[guests laughing, applauding]

910
01:09:39,216 --> 01:09:42,636
…we offer the ladies of this fair city
our first bachelor to be placed

911
01:09:42,720 --> 01:09:46,182
up on the auction block,
our host, Jonathan Devereaux.

912
01:09:46,265 --> 01:09:50,687
[guests cheering, applauding]

913
01:09:50,770 --> 01:09:53,606
[Louis] Where is that man?
Where is that man?

914
01:09:54,941 --> 01:09:56,859
-Hey, Jonathan.
-Thank you, Louis.

915
01:09:58,152 --> 01:10:01,364
-You all having a good time?
-[guests] Yeah!

916
01:10:02,031 --> 01:10:04,450
Now then, ladies, uh,
what you see before you

917
01:10:04,534 --> 01:10:06,619
is a moderately
presentable man in his thirties,

918
01:10:06,703 --> 01:10:10,832
given to unhealthy thoughts
and a dissipated lifestyle.

919
01:10:10,915 --> 01:10:11,791
[ladies laughing]

920
01:10:11,874 --> 01:10:15,128
With, and this is what's gonna
cost you the really big money.

921
01:10:15,211 --> 01:10:19,757
[guests cheering, applauding]

922
01:10:19,841 --> 01:10:25,346
-Absolutely no redeeming moral virtue.
-[guests laughing]

923
01:10:25,972 --> 01:10:27,140
Five hundred.

924
01:10:27,223 --> 01:10:29,142
Dear woman, my cuff links
cost more than that.

925
01:10:29,225 --> 01:10:31,769
-[guests laughing]
-Do I hear a 1,000?

926
01:10:31,853 --> 01:10:34,105
-A thousand.
-Thank you.

927
01:10:34,188 --> 01:10:36,357
-Ooh!
-[guests applauding]

928
01:10:36,441 --> 01:10:38,401
-Mm!
-Two thousand.

929
01:10:38,484 --> 01:10:40,945
[guests gasping, applauding]

930
01:10:41,028 --> 01:10:43,781
All right, now, did I just hear the voice
of the charming Miss Monroe?

931
01:10:43,865 --> 01:10:46,784
'Cause I was just starting to worry,
beginning to think you didn't care.

932
01:10:46,868 --> 01:10:48,244
[Libby] Twenty-five hundred.

933
01:10:48,327 --> 01:10:51,789
[guests gasping]

934
01:10:52,790 --> 01:10:54,959
Twenty-five hundred. We have a new bidder.

935
01:10:56,043 --> 01:10:58,671
-Twenty-five hundred.
-Three thousand.

936
01:10:58,755 --> 01:11:00,548
[guests applauding]

937
01:11:00,631 --> 01:11:02,967
-Five thousand.
-[guests gasping]

938
01:11:03,050 --> 01:11:07,346
[applauding]

939
01:11:10,725 --> 01:11:12,268
Fifty-five hundred.

940
01:11:12,351 --> 01:11:15,062
[guests hooting, murmuring]

941
01:11:16,773 --> 01:11:21,903
We have 5,500. Will, uh,
will the lady take us to six?

942
01:11:24,071 --> 01:11:25,615
Ten thousand dollars.

943
01:11:25,698 --> 01:11:27,575
[guests exclaiming]

944
01:11:27,658 --> 01:11:31,871
[applauding]

945
01:11:31,954 --> 01:11:35,124
Well, see, at last,
someone who knows my true value.

946
01:11:35,208 --> 01:11:37,293
-[guests laughing]
-[Nick] Now, Miss Monroe,

947
01:11:37,376 --> 01:11:40,797
I believe the bid
is to you at 10,500 dollars.

948
01:11:42,298 --> 01:11:45,551
Well, you can have him, honey.
Believe me, he ain't worth that much.

949
01:11:45,635 --> 01:11:47,386
I know from personal experience.

950
01:11:47,470 --> 01:11:50,181
-[guests exclaiming]
-Yeah. Thank you, honey.

951
01:11:50,681 --> 01:11:52,099
All right, going once.

952
01:11:52,892 --> 01:11:54,018
Going twice.

953
01:11:56,020 --> 01:11:58,064
-Sold to the woman in the back.
-Sold!

954
01:11:58,147 --> 01:12:00,608
-[guests applauding]
-[Nick] Ten thousand dollars.

955
01:12:04,654 --> 01:12:07,824
Would you like to come forward
and claim your prize, young lady?

956
01:12:08,574 --> 01:12:10,201
[dramatic music playing]

957
01:12:15,414 --> 01:12:16,582
Hello, Nick.

958
01:12:23,881 --> 01:12:25,842
Well, aren't you gonna give me a kiss?

959
01:12:27,051 --> 01:12:28,344
I think I've earned it.

960
01:12:31,889 --> 01:12:35,518
[guests murmuring, booing]

961
01:12:39,105 --> 01:12:42,358
[applauding]

962
01:12:43,860 --> 01:12:47,363
-And now…
-I'll make this real easy for you, Nick.

963
01:12:47,446 --> 01:12:52,076
I'll make you an offer you can't refuse.
You used to love a good deal, didn't you?

964
01:12:52,910 --> 01:12:55,246
-Can we just take this someplace private?
-I don't think so.

965
01:12:55,329 --> 01:12:57,081
I remember what happened
the last time we were alone.

966
01:12:57,164 --> 01:12:58,457
-I don't believe we've met.
-[sighs]

967
01:12:58,541 --> 01:13:01,544
-I'm Suzanne Monroe.
-I'm Libby. I'm his wife.

968
01:13:03,671 --> 01:13:05,673
Well, Jonathan!

969
01:13:06,340 --> 01:13:08,759
A minute ago a bachelor,
and now you're married.

970
01:13:08,843 --> 01:13:10,595
You don't waste any time.

971
01:13:12,054 --> 01:13:13,514
-You been in New Orleans long?
-She's, uh--

972
01:13:13,598 --> 01:13:15,683
I'm just passing through town
to pick up my child.

973
01:13:15,766 --> 01:13:17,768
-I'll be leaving very soon.
-How nice.

974
01:13:17,852 --> 01:13:20,479
We're finally putting the past behind us
and moving on with our lives,

975
01:13:20,563 --> 01:13:23,107
-aren't we, Jonathan?
-Sure.

976
01:13:23,941 --> 01:13:25,151
I do have one question though.

977
01:13:25,234 --> 01:13:28,112
How long were Angie and you fucking
before you decided to get rid of me?

978
01:13:28,195 --> 01:13:29,196
[clears throat]

979
01:13:32,074 --> 01:13:33,034
Would you excuse us, please?

980
01:13:33,117 --> 01:13:34,827
Oh, yeah, sure. Go ahead.

981
01:13:37,330 --> 01:13:39,081
-Where is he, Nick?
-Libby. Libby--

982
01:13:39,165 --> 01:13:41,334
You destroyed my life,
and I will destroy yours

983
01:13:41,417 --> 01:13:44,253
unless you give me Matty.
That's all I want.

984
01:13:44,337 --> 01:13:46,339
[Nick] Listen,
let me explain something to you.

985
01:13:46,422 --> 01:13:48,382
You have to understand something.
We were going under.

986
01:13:48,466 --> 01:13:50,134
We were gonna lose everything.

987
01:13:51,385 --> 01:13:53,429
If I'd had any guts,
I would have killed myself,

988
01:13:53,512 --> 01:13:56,933
but I was trying to protect you.
That's why I got the life insurance.

989
01:13:57,683 --> 01:14:01,312
So I would be out of the picture
and you and Matty would be okay.

990
01:14:02,021 --> 01:14:05,066
And I just never believed
they would convict you.

991
01:14:06,359 --> 01:14:07,485
They did, Nick.

992
01:14:09,028 --> 01:14:13,741
And the thing with Angie happened later.
It was just-- It was a nightmare.

993
01:14:15,326 --> 01:14:17,828
And the worst part of it
was being away from you.

994
01:14:17,912 --> 01:14:19,580
So is that why you killed her?

995
01:14:19,664 --> 01:14:21,832
-[guests applauding]
-[chuckles]

996
01:14:22,959 --> 01:14:26,253
-That was an accident.
-Nice try, Nick. I'm not buying.

997
01:14:26,337 --> 01:14:27,588
It's bullshit.

998
01:14:27,672 --> 01:14:31,050
-I will swear on the life of our son.
-Oh, don't you fucking dare.

999
01:14:31,592 --> 01:14:36,138
[scoffs] You can keep your hotel,
your fancy accent and your new name.

1000
01:14:36,222 --> 01:14:38,099
-Just give me Matty.
-I understand.

1001
01:14:38,182 --> 01:14:39,642
No. Now.

1002
01:14:39,725 --> 01:14:41,894
-Give him to me now.
-Libby, it's the middle of the night.

1003
01:14:41,978 --> 01:14:43,930
-I can't just walk away from here.
-[Libby] Do you think I'm stupid?

1004
01:14:44,055 --> 01:14:46,857
-No. I don't think you're stupid.
-I won't let you slip away once again.

1005
01:14:46,941 --> 01:14:48,401
It's too far to Matty's school.

1006
01:14:48,484 --> 01:14:52,029
-And you've got to be patient.
-I've been patient for six years.

1007
01:14:52,113 --> 01:14:54,532
-[bidder] Do I hear 2,000?
-I want my child.

1008
01:14:55,199 --> 01:14:58,494
Ah! Thank you. You're a beautiful woman.

1009
01:14:58,577 --> 01:15:01,497
I'll call you tomorrow, Nick.
No screwing around.

1010
01:15:01,580 --> 01:15:06,168
[bidder] Going twice.
Okay, 2,000 for the lady in red.

1011
01:15:06,252 --> 01:15:08,295
[Travis] Excuse me.
Do you know where Mr. Devereaux is?

1012
01:15:08,379 --> 01:15:10,006
-[waiter] He's at the bar, sir.
-Over here?

1013
01:15:10,089 --> 01:15:11,757
-[waiter] Yes, sir.
-Thank you.

1014
01:15:11,841 --> 01:15:13,634
[bidder] You ready to spend
some more money?

1015
01:15:13,718 --> 01:15:16,095
Who's gonna start us off? Who's gonna go?

1016
01:15:16,178 --> 01:15:19,682
[guests applauding]

1017
01:15:22,351 --> 01:15:25,438
I'm sorry. Oh, thank you, Marcel.

1018
01:15:25,563 --> 01:15:27,606
-Can I offer you a drink?
-Oh, no thanks.

1019
01:15:27,690 --> 01:15:30,317
Wait a second. Let me guess.
I take you for scotch and soda.

1020
01:15:30,401 --> 01:15:33,654
-Huh?
-Well, I'll have a Diet Coke, please.

1021
01:15:33,779 --> 01:15:36,490
Well, all right, but I bet you used
to drink and now you're on the wagon.

1022
01:15:36,574 --> 01:15:37,825
Ten dollars says I'm right.

1023
01:15:37,908 --> 01:15:39,243
You sure you've never seen
this woman before?

1024
01:15:39,326 --> 01:15:40,953
-No, I'm positive.
-Okay.

1025
01:15:41,037 --> 01:15:43,873
Let me get it straight, though.
She believes that I am her husband.

1026
01:15:43,956 --> 01:15:45,791
-Oh, yeah.
-Whom she killed.

1027
01:15:45,875 --> 01:15:46,917
Yes, sir.

1028
01:15:48,753 --> 01:15:50,504
That's… that's pretty far-fetched.

1029
01:15:50,588 --> 01:15:52,673
Uh… Far-fetched or not,
she is in New Orleans,

1030
01:15:52,757 --> 01:15:54,800
She does have a gun
and she is looking for you.

1031
01:15:54,884 --> 01:15:57,136
Well, thank you.
I'll alert our security people.

1032
01:15:57,219 --> 01:15:58,471
-You do that.
-[thunder rumbling]

1033
01:15:58,554 --> 01:16:01,182
-[indistinct chatter]
-[Cajun music playing]

1034
01:16:15,488 --> 01:16:17,364
Cops have been passing these out.

1035
01:16:22,244 --> 01:16:24,497
No reward. Screw 'em.

1036
01:16:27,583 --> 01:16:29,835
You're gonna be posted
in every hotel in town.

1037
01:16:30,669 --> 01:16:32,421
So much for a good night's sleep.

1038
01:16:40,638 --> 01:16:43,265
Take this. Get out of here.

1039
01:16:48,062 --> 01:16:49,188
Thanks a lot.

1040
01:17:13,629 --> 01:17:15,881
[Dixieland music playing]

1041
01:17:25,891 --> 01:17:27,852
Let's go, Lehman. We spotted your girl.

1042
01:17:45,828 --> 01:17:47,580
[bells clanging]

1043
01:17:49,540 --> 01:17:53,043
-[thunder clapping]
-[horse whinnies]

1044
01:18:01,635 --> 01:18:02,970
Where'd she go, Dilbert?

1045
01:18:09,643 --> 01:18:10,644
Hey!

1046
01:18:23,657 --> 01:18:24,658
Hey!

1047
01:18:31,373 --> 01:18:32,291
Hey!

1048
01:18:57,858 --> 01:18:58,776
Hey!

1049
01:19:01,695 --> 01:19:03,864
-Hey!
-I'm sorry.

1050
01:19:03,948 --> 01:19:06,450
-What do you think you're doing?
-I'm very sorry, ma'am.

1051
01:19:06,533 --> 01:19:09,411
I thought you were somebody else.
It was a case of mistaken identity.

1052
01:19:09,495 --> 01:19:12,331
-Have a good evening.
-I take it that ain't her.

1053
01:19:20,256 --> 01:19:21,340
[music concludes]

1054
01:19:21,423 --> 01:19:24,385
[indistinct chatter]

1055
01:19:27,221 --> 01:19:29,306
-[Nick] Mr. Lehman.
-[chuckles]

1056
01:19:30,057 --> 01:19:30,975
Come in.

1057
01:19:31,058 --> 01:19:33,644
-Thank you.
-May I offer you a Cuban cigar?

1058
01:19:33,727 --> 01:19:34,937
Oh, no thanks.

1059
01:19:36,063 --> 01:19:40,150
Well, as you can see,
I'm alive and kicking.

1060
01:19:40,234 --> 01:19:41,819
[chuckles] Yeah.

1061
01:19:43,404 --> 01:19:44,947
So what can I do for you this morning?

1062
01:19:45,030 --> 01:19:47,825
We spotted the Parsons woman
in the quarter last night.

1063
01:19:48,534 --> 01:19:52,371
She got away. I just came by
to find out if you'd heard from her.

1064
01:19:53,372 --> 01:19:54,581
Not a peep.

1065
01:19:54,665 --> 01:19:57,793
Do you have any idea
why she's fixated her lunacy on you?

1066
01:19:58,669 --> 01:20:00,629
Well, the world's full of crazy people,
am I right?

1067
01:20:00,713 --> 01:20:05,301
Oh, yes, you are right. [laughs]
Truer words were never spoken.

1068
01:20:06,885 --> 01:20:08,679
Those are nice pictures there.

1069
01:20:09,471 --> 01:20:11,056
Did your kids do them?

1070
01:20:12,766 --> 01:20:14,893
Uh… No. [chuckles]

1071
01:20:16,145 --> 01:20:19,523
Those pictures are by
a very great artist named Kandinsky.

1072
01:20:19,606 --> 01:20:21,025
Oh.

1073
01:20:21,108 --> 01:20:23,277
But why do I think you already knew that?

1074
01:20:26,405 --> 01:20:27,531
[telephone ringing]

1075
01:20:28,782 --> 01:20:29,992
Excuse me for a second.

1076
01:20:30,701 --> 01:20:31,785
Yes?

1077
01:20:36,081 --> 01:20:37,166
This is a business call.

1078
01:20:37,249 --> 01:20:38,959
Oh, I'm sorry. [chuckles]

1079
01:20:39,043 --> 01:20:41,545
I hope you'll excuse me.
You let yourself out that back door.

1080
01:20:41,628 --> 01:20:42,880
It leads down to the kitchen.

1081
01:20:42,963 --> 01:20:45,132
Yeah. Get the chef to fix you
a fabulous New Orleans breakfast.

1082
01:20:45,215 --> 01:20:47,301
-Thanks.
-[Nick] I recommend the Eggs St. Jacques.

1083
01:20:47,384 --> 01:20:49,261
-Oh, boy. That sounds good.
-[Nick] Mm-hmm. I have your card.

1084
01:20:49,345 --> 01:20:50,346
Okay.

1085
01:20:54,808 --> 01:20:57,353
Morning, darling.
I hope you had a nice night.

1086
01:20:57,436 --> 01:21:01,857
I want you to bring Matty
to Lafayette Cemetery number three.

1087
01:21:01,940 --> 01:21:04,860
A cemetery?
That's an odd choice for a reunion.

1088
01:21:04,943 --> 01:21:08,489
It's a big tourist place, Nick.
Lot of people around.

1089
01:21:08,572 --> 01:21:12,326
You're a smart girl.
I can have him there by 4:00.

1090
01:21:13,911 --> 01:21:17,790
[jazz band playing "St. James Infirmary"]

1091
01:21:37,518 --> 01:21:41,814
[indistinct chatter]

1092
01:21:52,866 --> 01:21:54,243
Where's Matty?

1093
01:21:54,952 --> 01:21:57,079
Relax. He's-- He was nervous.

1094
01:21:57,162 --> 01:21:59,998
So I just told him
he could go play inside.

1095
01:22:07,631 --> 01:22:08,715
There he is.

1096
01:22:10,384 --> 01:22:12,719
Matty? Come over here, son.

1097
01:22:14,972 --> 01:22:16,181
Oh, geez. Matty--

1098
01:22:16,265 --> 01:22:18,600
-Okay, I'll get him for you.
-No! No.

1099
01:22:19,643 --> 01:22:21,145
That's something I want to do.

1100
01:22:25,482 --> 01:22:26,567
Matty?

1101
01:22:32,739 --> 01:22:33,824
Matty?

1102
01:22:34,950 --> 01:22:36,243
Hey, kiddo.

1103
01:22:40,205 --> 01:22:41,290
Hey, Matty!

1104
01:23:38,597 --> 01:23:39,681
Matty?

1105
01:23:41,725 --> 01:23:43,352
[stammers] Matty, it's mommy.

1106
01:23:46,230 --> 01:23:48,065
[gasps, groans]

1107
01:24:05,582 --> 01:24:08,669
[Jim] Mr. Lehman,
you're gonna have to learn to relax, son.

1108
01:24:08,752 --> 01:24:12,256
What have you got your panties
in such a twist about, anyhow?

1109
01:24:12,339 --> 01:24:14,800
-[keyboard clacking]
-[sighs]

1110
01:24:14,883 --> 01:24:17,761
You ever arrest anybody
you thought was innocent, Mangold?

1111
01:24:18,929 --> 01:24:19,805
Nope.

1112
01:24:21,557 --> 01:24:23,517
-[computer beeping]
-[Travis sighs]

1113
01:24:24,601 --> 01:24:27,104
'Course there's no information
on Jonathan Devereaux

1114
01:24:27,187 --> 01:24:28,188
that's over three years old.

1115
01:24:28,272 --> 01:24:31,400
-Three years ago the guy didn't exist.
-So he changed his name.

1116
01:24:32,150 --> 01:24:34,069
Lots of folks change their names, Lehman.

1117
01:24:34,152 --> 01:24:36,071
-That don't make 'em criminals.
-Yeah, but I'm betting

1118
01:24:36,154 --> 01:24:38,657
he changed it from Simon Ryder,
and before that, Nick Parsons.

1119
01:24:38,740 --> 01:24:40,242
-But you can't prove it.
-No.

1120
01:24:41,076 --> 01:24:44,621
[band playing "Red River Valley"]

1121
01:25:06,560 --> 01:25:09,730
[indistinct chatter]

1122
01:25:09,813 --> 01:25:12,065
Hey! Is that long distance?

1123
01:25:13,317 --> 01:25:16,320
Bill me. Lucy, hi. This is Travis. Listen.

1124
01:25:17,070 --> 01:25:20,657
I want you to get the D.M.V. to fax me
a Washington driver's license photograph

1125
01:25:20,741 --> 01:25:24,077
<i>of one Nicholas Parsons.</i>
<i>I'm at the New Orleans Police Department.</i>

1126
01:25:24,161 --> 01:25:25,454
Travis, you better talk

1127
01:25:25,537 --> 01:25:26,663
-to Mr. Carruthers.
-Travis!

1128
01:25:26,747 --> 01:25:29,166
-His colon is twisted in a knot.
-Give me that.

1129
01:25:30,542 --> 01:25:32,294
I've had to cover
your office for you, Travis.

1130
01:25:32,377 --> 01:25:34,588
<i>-Where the hell are you?</i>
-Listen to me, Karl.

1131
01:25:34,671 --> 01:25:36,590
I think maybe this Parsons woman
has been telling the truth.

1132
01:25:36,673 --> 01:25:38,342
[Karl] <i>You're not</i>
<i>a law professor anymore, Travis.</i>

1133
01:25:38,425 --> 01:25:40,385
You're barely even a parole officer.

1134
01:25:40,469 --> 01:25:43,138
-So stop playing <i>Mission Impossible </i>and--
-[Travis]<i> All I need</i>

1135
01:25:43,221 --> 01:25:46,266
is a D.M.V. Driver's license photograph
of Nicholas Parsons.

1136
01:25:46,350 --> 01:25:48,602
You get back here today,

1137
01:25:48,685 --> 01:25:51,855
because tomorrow,
you're going in front of the commission.

1138
01:25:51,938 --> 01:25:55,984
Karl, I know I'm right.
You give me a chance, okay?

1139
01:25:57,110 --> 01:26:00,822
Now, I'm asking you politely.
You send me the goddamn picture!

1140
01:26:04,826 --> 01:26:08,038
-[Libby groans]
-[lighter flicking]

1141
01:26:09,748 --> 01:26:10,707
[sniffs]

1142
01:26:17,047 --> 01:26:20,926
[gasps, pants]

1143
01:26:24,096 --> 01:26:26,056
[eerie music playing]

1144
01:26:26,139 --> 01:26:31,645
[whimpers]

1145
01:26:39,027 --> 01:26:42,489
[pants]

1146
01:26:52,207 --> 01:26:53,500
[moans]

1147
01:26:58,004 --> 01:27:01,007
-[casket pounding]
-[Libby grunting]

1148
01:27:04,136 --> 01:27:07,681
[grunts]

1149
01:27:59,524 --> 01:28:01,693
-[gunshot]
-[Libby grunts]

1150
01:28:14,623 --> 01:28:19,669
[grunts]

1151
01:28:29,846 --> 01:28:31,264
Hey!

1152
01:28:31,348 --> 01:28:33,225
-[door pounding]
-[Libby] Hey!

1153
01:28:34,392 --> 01:28:35,894
[grunts]

1154
01:28:40,941 --> 01:28:42,275
[grunts]

1155
01:28:42,359 --> 01:28:44,694
-[printer humming]
-[indistinct chatter]

1156
01:28:51,243 --> 01:28:52,661
It's not him.

1157
01:28:52,744 --> 01:28:54,788
[Jim] See, Lehman, the thing is,
every now and again,

1158
01:28:54,871 --> 01:28:56,790
we all want to believe in something.

1159
01:28:56,873 --> 01:28:59,793
But we just keep forgetting
that 99.9% of the time,

1160
01:28:59,876 --> 01:29:02,087
life just flat don't work out.

1161
01:29:02,170 --> 01:29:05,799
I hadn't thought of that, Mangold.
Thanks. I feel a lot better now.

1162
01:29:05,882 --> 01:29:07,133
Any time, hoss. Any time.

1163
01:29:07,717 --> 01:29:10,846
-[indistinct chatter]
-[tense music playing]

1164
01:29:19,271 --> 01:29:21,064
Hold it. Hold it right here.

1165
01:29:30,490 --> 01:29:31,700
[sighs]

1166
01:29:46,381 --> 01:29:47,340
[gasps]

1167
01:29:48,717 --> 01:29:50,802
-It's over, Libby.
-[music fades]

1168
01:29:50,886 --> 01:29:54,014
-[solemn music playing]
-[sobs] Oh, Travis.

1169
01:29:58,727 --> 01:30:02,564
[wails]

1170
01:30:08,153 --> 01:30:09,696
[indistinct chatter]

1171
01:30:22,208 --> 01:30:23,209
Messages.

1172
01:30:25,253 --> 01:30:26,254
Thank you.

1173
01:30:28,006 --> 01:30:30,842
-[Travis] Mr. Devereaux?
-Mr. Lehman.

1174
01:30:30,926 --> 01:30:33,053
I'm sorry. This is really not a good time.

1175
01:30:33,136 --> 01:30:34,220
I understand.

1176
01:30:35,055 --> 01:30:36,806
You know a lot of people
feel that way about me.

1177
01:30:36,890 --> 01:30:38,391
-But I have good news.
-Mm-hmm?

1178
01:30:40,894 --> 01:30:42,145
Won't take long.

1179
01:30:45,440 --> 01:30:47,275
-Well?
-Well…

1180
01:30:49,110 --> 01:30:51,863
Turns out I owe you
an apology, Mr. Devereaux.

1181
01:30:53,615 --> 01:30:56,242
After our last conversation
I started thinking

1182
01:30:56,326 --> 01:30:59,913
maybe that Parsons woman is telling
the truth about who you used to be.

1183
01:31:01,122 --> 01:31:04,709
So I asked the Washington State
Department of Motor Vehicles

1184
01:31:04,793 --> 01:31:09,255
to send me a driver's license photograph
of Nicholas Parsons.

1185
01:31:10,590 --> 01:31:12,717
-And?
-And this is what came up.

1186
01:31:19,349 --> 01:31:20,767
[laughs]

1187
01:31:22,852 --> 01:31:23,728
Well…

1188
01:31:26,481 --> 01:31:28,400
we all make mistakes.
There's no harm done.

1189
01:31:28,483 --> 01:31:30,860
[Travis] Then I thought about it
some more, and it occurred to me

1190
01:31:30,944 --> 01:31:35,156
what a common name Nicolas Parsons is.
You know, it turns out there were six.

1191
01:31:35,824 --> 01:31:36,866
And this…

1192
01:31:38,535 --> 01:31:39,661
was number three.

1193
01:31:43,665 --> 01:31:45,041
I never liked that picture.

1194
01:31:48,795 --> 01:31:51,214
So, Mr. Lehman,
you came here to make a deal

1195
01:31:51,923 --> 01:31:54,884
otherwise, I guess you would have
gone straight to the police.

1196
01:31:54,968 --> 01:31:57,721
-So, question is, what's your price?
-A million dollars.

1197
01:31:58,888 --> 01:32:01,099
-[laughs]
-It's a nice round figure, right?

1198
01:32:02,058 --> 01:32:03,018
Uh…

1199
01:32:06,646 --> 01:32:09,691
All right. But you're gonna have
to give me a couple of days.

1200
01:32:09,774 --> 01:32:11,735
No way. One million dollars, right now.

1201
01:32:12,694 --> 01:32:15,155
Mr. Lehman, it's nine o'clock at night.

1202
01:32:15,238 --> 01:32:17,032
I can't just-- [snaps fingers]

1203
01:32:20,535 --> 01:32:23,121
-Wait a minute. Wait a minute. Wait.
-[keypad beeps]

1204
01:32:24,289 --> 01:32:26,666
I have 100,000 dollars in the safe here.

1205
01:32:27,459 --> 01:32:28,960
And you can have that now.

1206
01:32:30,295 --> 01:32:31,880
I'll get you the rest tomorrow.

1207
01:32:33,673 --> 01:32:34,674
You got a deal.

1208
01:32:37,510 --> 01:32:40,263
We do have one other problem,
and that's Mrs. Parsons.

1209
01:32:40,346 --> 01:32:42,724
She could still make
a lot of trouble for us, even from prison.

1210
01:32:42,807 --> 01:32:46,061
-[chuckles] And I really don't need that.
-Well, I think I've solved that problem.

1211
01:32:46,144 --> 01:32:47,020
What do you mean?

1212
01:32:47,103 --> 01:32:49,689
Let's just say the problem
has been buried.

1213
01:32:49,773 --> 01:32:52,817
-Really?
-She's gone, I promise you.

1214
01:32:53,443 --> 01:32:55,528
[tense music playing]

1215
01:33:03,620 --> 01:33:05,955
You're not very good
at keeping promises, Nick.

1216
01:33:07,248 --> 01:33:08,666
You gonna do something?

1217
01:33:08,750 --> 01:33:11,878
What are you talking to me for?
She's the one with the gun.

1218
01:33:19,844 --> 01:33:21,554
They're tough in Louisiana, Libby.

1219
01:33:22,972 --> 01:33:25,308
You shoot me,
they'll give you the gas chamber.

1220
01:33:25,391 --> 01:33:26,518
No, they won't.

1221
01:33:27,185 --> 01:33:30,355
It's called double jeopardy.
I learned a few things in prison, Nick.

1222
01:33:30,438 --> 01:33:33,233
I could shoot you in the middle
of Mardi Gras and they can't touch me.

1223
01:33:33,316 --> 01:33:35,985
As an ex-law professor,
I can assure you she is right.

1224
01:33:40,448 --> 01:33:41,616
Where's my son?

1225
01:33:44,327 --> 01:33:46,913
In St. Albans School
in Georgia, all right?

1226
01:33:48,832 --> 01:33:50,542
You have your son back.
You got what you want.

1227
01:33:50,625 --> 01:33:51,709
[gunshot]

1228
01:33:53,253 --> 01:33:54,462
[music concludes]

1229
01:34:01,678 --> 01:34:04,639
I haven't felt that good
in six years. [laughs]

1230
01:34:07,976 --> 01:34:11,146
I don't want to kill you, Nick.
I just want you to suffer like I suffered.

1231
01:34:11,229 --> 01:34:13,898
What she means, Nick, is,
you're going to prison…

1232
01:34:14,941 --> 01:34:15,859
for murder.

1233
01:34:16,359 --> 01:34:18,570
-Who did I supposedly murder?
-Me.

1234
01:34:22,532 --> 01:34:25,743
-All you've got is an old fax photo.
-Which supplies the motive.

1235
01:34:25,827 --> 01:34:28,204
Your wife, whom you had framed,
tracks you down,

1236
01:34:28,288 --> 01:34:30,915
and to keep her
from exposing you, you kill her.

1237
01:34:30,999 --> 01:34:33,293
-You won't get away with it.
-[tape rewinding]

1238
01:34:33,376 --> 01:34:35,336
[Nick's voice on tape]
<i>Well, I think I've solved that problem.</i>

1239
01:34:35,420 --> 01:34:37,005
-[Travis] <i>What do you mean?</i>
-[Nick] <i>Let's just say</i>

1240
01:34:37,088 --> 01:34:38,423
<i>the problem has been buried.</i>

1241
01:34:38,506 --> 01:34:41,342
-[Travis] <i>Really?</i>
-[Nick] <i>She's gone, I promise you.</i>

1242
01:34:41,426 --> 01:34:42,427
[clicks off]

1243
01:34:44,596 --> 01:34:46,723
Taped confessions are very persuasive
in court, Nick,

1244
01:34:46,806 --> 01:34:49,309
and of course
there is the physical evidence

1245
01:34:49,392 --> 01:34:51,227
that we're gonna put
in the trunk of your car.

1246
01:34:51,311 --> 01:34:54,189
A shovel, hair, my fingerprints,
a little blood.

1247
01:34:54,272 --> 01:34:55,273
Don't forget the gasoline.

1248
01:34:55,356 --> 01:34:56,941
It'll look like you burned
and buried my body,

1249
01:34:57,025 --> 01:34:58,735
just like you say on the tape.

1250
01:34:59,861 --> 01:35:01,404
The prosecution rests.

1251
01:35:03,198 --> 01:35:04,365
You better get out of here.

1252
01:35:04,449 --> 01:35:06,034
Nobody wants a dead woman
walking around when the police

1253
01:35:06,117 --> 01:35:08,286
are trying to arrest a guy for her murder.

1254
01:35:09,954 --> 01:35:11,831
Wait a minute. I'll take that gun.

1255
01:35:12,373 --> 01:35:13,833
-[gunshot]
-[gasps]

1256
01:35:13,917 --> 01:35:15,960
[intense music playing]

1257
01:35:16,044 --> 01:35:20,131
-[gunshots firing]
-[pants]

1258
01:35:20,798 --> 01:35:22,133
[groans]

1259
01:35:23,426 --> 01:35:25,094
No. [gasps]

1260
01:35:33,019 --> 01:35:36,856
-[Travis grunts]
-[glass shatters]

1261
01:35:37,857 --> 01:35:41,194
[both grunt]

1262
01:35:46,699 --> 01:35:47,867
[Travis grunts]

1263
01:35:49,410 --> 01:35:51,788
-[Nick grunts]
-[groans]

1264
01:35:58,253 --> 01:36:01,214
[pants]

1265
01:36:03,466 --> 01:36:04,467
[gunshot]

1266
01:36:07,011 --> 01:36:08,096
[gunshot]

1267
01:36:19,274 --> 01:36:20,650
[music concludes]

1268
01:36:20,733 --> 01:36:23,361
[indistinct chatter]

1269
01:36:32,412 --> 01:36:34,080
Well, Lehman, you gonna live?

1270
01:36:36,666 --> 01:36:38,626
-[Jim laughing]
-I doubt it.

1271
01:36:38,710 --> 01:36:41,879
Ms. Parsons,
since you are still legally his wife,

1272
01:36:41,963 --> 01:36:44,799
I expect you just inherited yourself
a right fine little hotel here.

1273
01:36:44,882 --> 01:36:46,050
Not interested.

1274
01:36:47,468 --> 01:36:49,012
[groans]

1275
01:36:54,934 --> 01:36:56,894
I guess I'm gonna take off now.

1276
01:36:56,978 --> 01:37:00,148
No. No, you're not.

1277
01:37:00,231 --> 01:37:02,233
You're a parole violator.
You're in my custody.

1278
01:37:02,317 --> 01:37:04,277
You're going with me to Seattle,

1279
01:37:05,611 --> 01:37:08,781
-where I will demand a full pardon…
-[chuckles]

1280
01:37:09,324 --> 01:37:11,868
…and a parade, and a little pink poodle…

1281
01:37:13,202 --> 01:37:16,289
-on a keychain.
-[laughs]

1282
01:37:18,958 --> 01:37:21,377
-[birds chirping]
-[indistinct chatter]

1283
01:37:25,882 --> 01:37:28,259
[student shouting] Come on, Ryan, pass it!

1284
01:37:30,470 --> 01:37:31,554
[whistle blows]

1285
01:37:43,232 --> 01:37:44,484
What are you waiting for?

1286
01:37:46,152 --> 01:37:47,028
Go on.

1287
01:37:49,822 --> 01:37:52,950
I don't know if I've ever been
so scared in my whole life.

1288
01:37:54,494 --> 01:37:57,622
I think a big part of me never thought
I'd\ really find him.

1289
01:38:00,291 --> 01:38:02,001
What if he doesn't recognize me?

1290
01:38:03,169 --> 01:38:05,421
-I mean, maybe after all this time--
-Damn, woman!

1291
01:38:05,505 --> 01:38:07,840
Because of you, I have lost
a perfectly good used car,

1292
01:38:07,924 --> 01:38:09,384
and a not-so-good job.

1293
01:38:09,467 --> 01:38:13,763
If you don't go to this kid right now,
I'm gonna have you arrested for stupidity.

1294
01:38:13,846 --> 01:38:14,806
Go on.

1295
01:38:15,390 --> 01:38:17,392
[inhales, sighs softly]

1296
01:38:20,561 --> 01:38:21,687
Thanks, Lehman.

1297
01:38:23,356 --> 01:38:25,233
-You saved my life.
-[Travis chuckles]

1298
01:38:29,404 --> 01:38:30,613
You saved mine too.

1299
01:38:31,656 --> 01:38:35,451
[indistinct clamor]

1300
01:38:44,710 --> 01:38:47,505
-Coach Matthews. How you doing?
-Nice to meet you.

1301
01:38:48,798 --> 01:38:50,341
It'll be halftime soon.

1302
01:38:52,468 --> 01:38:54,387
[soft music playing]

1303
01:39:06,315 --> 01:39:08,609
-[whistle blows]
-[Coach Matthews] Halftime!

1304
01:39:08,693 --> 01:39:09,861
Matty.

1305
01:39:09,944 --> 01:39:12,238
[soft music playing]

1306
01:39:12,321 --> 01:39:13,197
Matty.

1307
01:39:28,004 --> 01:39:29,255
Hi.

1308
01:39:34,010 --> 01:39:35,470
Do you know who I am?

1309
01:39:37,847 --> 01:39:40,099
[chuckles] They told me you were dead.

1310
01:39:40,183 --> 01:39:41,601
[gasps]

1311
01:39:42,852 --> 01:39:43,936
No, sweetheart.

1312
01:39:46,814 --> 01:39:47,857
[exhales]

1313
01:39:49,317 --> 01:39:50,485
[chuckles]

1314
01:39:59,410 --> 01:40:00,536
[chuckles]

1315
01:40:21,140 --> 01:40:22,266
[chuckles]

1316
01:40:29,106 --> 01:40:30,274
[music concludes]

1317
01:40:32,235 --> 01:40:34,195
[instrumental music playing]

1318
01:42:11,042 --> 01:42:13,461
-[music fades]
-[dramatic music playing]

1319
01:43:38,713 --> 01:43:41,298
-[music fades]
-[solemn music playing]

1320
01:45:03,631 --> 01:45:05,007
[music concludes]

